<H3> <TI>     Asian Meeting on Fighting Seawater Pollution Ends in Xiamen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1311163393 Beijing XINHUA in English 1451 GMT 13 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW1311163393 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Xiamen, Nov 13 (XINHUA) -- The United Nations 
Development Program (UNDP) and the International Maritime 
Organization (IMO) reached an agreement on a program for East 
Asian marine pollution control here today. 
  This was the result of a meeting of representatives from 
over 
a dozen international organizations and East Asian nations to 
coordinate the fight against seawater pollution in East Asia. 
The project was sponsored by the UNDP and the Global 
Environment Foundation (GEF). 
  According to the agreement, the IMO, as an executive body of 
the agreement, will consult with East Asian countries about 
personnel training, funding, information exchange and the 
management of experimental zones. 
  The three-day meeting was held in this coastal city in East 
China's Fujian Province. 
  Three experimental zones were designated -- respectively in 
Xiamen, Malacca in Malaysia and Batangas in the Philippines -- 
to provide other East Asian countries with experience for the 
comprehensive control of coastal waters. 

</TEXT>

