<H3> <TI>     Guangdong Covers Half Landspace With Greenery </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1711011993 Beijing XINHUA in English 0105 GMT 17 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW1711011993 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guangdong, Nov 16 (XINHUA) -- Painstaking efforts 
over the past eight years have raised the forest coverage rate 
to 53 percent of the land space of south China's Guangdong 
Province, official sources said here today. 
  The sources said all 106 cities and counties of the province 
have met their afforestation tasks two years ahead of the 
official completion date. 
  In the past eight years since the launch of a ten-year 
afforestation program, the province has set up thousands of 
fruit, bamboo and tea plantations, plus large areas of timber 
forests. 
  In 1987, Guangdong had accumulated more timber reserves than 
it had to consume. 
  Successful afforestation work has also brought a boom in 
industrial development in many fields. The official said the 
province's annual income from fruit and other forest products 
exceeds 400 million U.S. dollars. 

</TEXT>

