<H3> <TI>   Sources Say Tokyo To Pledge Sustainable Forest Management </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1511103393 Tokyo KYODO in English 1000 GMT 15 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW1511103393 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Nov 15 KYODO -- Japan will outline a clear 
policy for conserving its forests through sustainable management 
at a board meeting of the International Timber Organization 
(ITTO) in Yokohama Tuesday [16 November], Forestry Agency 
sources said Monday. 
  Yoshio Hironaka, head of the agency's guidance division, 
will 
articulate Japan's wish to tackle forest depletion at home as 
well as abroad, the sources said. 
  Hironaka will explain that sustainable timber management 
continues to be a prime conservation goal of the government, 
they said. 
  Such management involves protecting existing forests and 
replanting felled areas while still making economic progress. 
  The ITTO member countries agreed at a meeting in June last 
year to promote sustainable forest management worldwide and not 
just in tropical regions. 
  European countries, the United States and Canada have 
already 
pledged to act on the agreement, the sources said. 
  The agency hopes that Japan's commitment will facilitate 
stalled talks between advanced and developing countries over 
revising the international tropical timber agreement which 
expires next March, they said. 
  The ITTO meeting in Yokohama started November 10 and 
continues until Wednesday with government and nongovernment 
representatives from countries producing or consuming tropical 
timber. 

</TEXT>

