<H3> <TI>   Japan Offers Funds To Curb Desertification </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1711034293 Tokyo KYODO in English 0317 GMT 17 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW1711034293 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, Nov 16 KYODO -- Japan told an international 
conference on Middle East environmental problems Tuesday [16 
November] it will contribute $530,000 to a program aimed at 
halting desertification. 
  Japan made the offer at the fourth meeting of a working 
group 
on the environment, one of five working groups operating in the 
multilateral track of the current Middle East peace process. 
  The startup funds would go toward a $9 million 
desertification control program proposed by the International 
Bank for Reconstruction and Development. 
  Japan served as the chair country for the meeting, at which 
it was decided to hold a meeting next February in Cairo to draft 
a set of standardized basic principles or ``codes of conduct'' 
for regional governments to adhere to when dealing with 
environmental issues. 
  Also considered was the establishment of an environmental 
agency by Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories set 
to be self-administered under the recent accord between Israel 
and the Palestine Liberation Organization. 
  Forty-three countries and two international organizations 
participated in the meeting. Syria and Lebanon skipped the 
session. 

</TEXT>

