<H3> <TI>   Report on Quality of Nation's Waters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1911054993 Tokyo KYODO in English 0253 GMT 19 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW1911054993 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Nov 19 KYODO -- Tokyo bay's water quality 
improved significantly in 1992, with the environmental quality 
standard increasing 10.5 percentage points over the previous 
year to 73.7 percent, Environment Agency officials said Friday. 
  The officials cited improved sewage systems along side 
rivers 
flowing into the bay. They also said the sewage treatment rate 
improved to around 65 percent in fiscal 1990 compared with 43 
percent in fiscal 1979. 
  The agency surveyed chemical oxygen demand as the indicator 
of water pollution in the bay. 
  The Tokyo Bay assessment was released Friday as part of an 
annual nationwide survey of water pollution in lakes, rivers and 
seas. 
  The quality standard in western Japan's Seto Inland Sea 
stood 
at 78.2 percent in 1992, the same as the previous year, the 
survey said. 
  The national average quality standard in sea areas hit 80.9 
percent, a slight increase of 0.7 percentage point over the 
previous year, according to the survey. 
  The average river water quality standard stood at the same 
level as the previous year, 75.4 percent, it said. 
  The quality standard for lakes and marshes improved by 2.3 
percentage points to 44.6 percent, the survey reported. 

</TEXT>

