<H3> <TI>   Sea of Japan Governors' Summit Proposed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2311094493 Tokyo KYODO in English 0926 GMT 23 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW2311094493 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Fukuoka, Nov 23 KYODO -- Representatives from 16 
prefectures facing the Sea of Japan proposed Tuesday [23 
November] holding a governors' summit in 1994 to discuss 
preservation of the environment and establishment of a social 
infrastructure in the region. 
  The proposal was made in a statement issued Tuesday at the 
end of a forum sponsored by the Social Democratic Party (SDP), 
the largest of seven parties in the ruling coalition. 
  The statement also called on the government, local 
autonomous 
bodies and universities to undertake studies to safeguard the 
environment and promote management of fishery resources. 
  The SDP hopes to convene the sea of Japan governors' summit 
around next June, a party official said. The party has already 
gained basic endorsement for the summit plan, the official said. 
  The governors of Fukuoka and Hokkaido, the largest of the 16 
prefectures facing the Sea of Japan, have both won elections 
under the SDP's backing. 
  During the two-day forum attended by some 220 people, 
academics, prefectural and municipal officials, international 
exchange experts, and fishery representatives discussed a wide 
range of themes concerning regional exchanges and development. 
  The Sea of Japan rim prefectures range from Hokkaido in the 
north to Fukuoka, Saga and Nagasaki Prefectures in the south. 
  Development in those prefectures, particularly on Honshu 
island, is far behind that of prefectures facing the Pacific 
which include Japan's three biggest business centers of Tokyo, 
Osaka and Nagoya. 

</TEXT>

