<F P=101> JAPAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Hosokawa Pledges Environmental Loan to Argentina </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0212111393 Tokyo KYODO in English 1026 GMT 2 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW0212111393 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Dec 2 KYODO -- Japan will loan up to 8.15 
billion yen to Argentina to support the nation's efforts to 
improve the environment, Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa said 
Thursday [2 December]. 
  Hosokawa made the pledge in a meeting with Argentine 
President Carlos Menem, according to Foreign Ministry officials. 
  The loan will be provided for Argentina's program to improve 
sanitary conditions along the Reconquista River, which runs 
north of the capital of Buenos Aires, the officials said. 
  The loan is part of Japan's plan to expand its Official 
Development Assistance (ODA) to 900 billion to 1 trillion yen 
over a five-year period from 1992. 
  Tokyo expressed its intention to expand its ODA at the U.N. 
Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED) in June last 
year, they said. 
  The loan will be extended in cooperation with the 
Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), they said. 

</TEXT>

