<F P=101> PHILIPPINES </F>
<H3> <TI>   Batangas Bay Slated for Marine Pollution Management Project </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0612061493 Manila BUSINESS WORLD in English 2 Dec 93 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> BK0612061493 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila BUSINESS WORLD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Maricris C. Carlos] </F>
  [Text] Batangas Bay has been chosen as one of three pilot 
areas in Asia to showcase a marine pollution management project 
geared at helping mitigate pollution damage in East Asian seas. 
  Once fully operational, it will be the first program of its 
kind where pollution and its risks are confronted and studied in 
depth for more systematic and effective management. 
  Cosponsored by the United Nations Development Programme 
(UNDP) and the Global Environment Facility (GEF), the project 
will have an initial funding of $8 billion. 
  The two other projects will be piloted in Xiamen Bay in 
China 
and Malacca Strait in Malaysia. 
  The project is designed to strengthen East Asia's capability 
in marine pollution management by demonstrating the 
effectiveness of an integrated coastal zone management approach. 
  The mechanism provides a conceptual framework within which 
the cumulative, multisectoral environmental consequences of 
industrialization can be managed to remain within tolerable 
limits. 
  With the project in place, rapidly industrializing countries 
in East Asia will have an idea on managing marine resources on a 
sustainable basis. 
  The program will support the development of a regional 
marine 
pollution information management and monitoring network. 
  It also seeks to strengthen the capacity of the region and 
the countries to enforce and comply with international 
conventions in controlling marine pollution. 
  Equally important, the project also aims to initiate 
sustainable financing options for marine pollution management. 
  The Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) 
will play the lead role in the project's implementation. 
  DENR is hopeful the project can also mitigate pollution 
damage in the waters of Manila Bay, Lingayen Bay, Tanon Strait, 
Calancan Bay, and Iligan Bay. 
  DENR's Robert Jara told BUSINESS WORLD one of the reasons 
Batangas Bay was chosen as a pilot area was on the active role 
of government and the private sector in protecting the bay's 
marine resources. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

