<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> THAILAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Surat Thani River's Lead Pollution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WN0077A Bangkok BAN MUANG in Thai 22 Oct 93 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> 94WN0077A </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BAN MUANG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Excerpt] Mr. Sombat Uitrakun, director of the Zone 11 
Environmental Health Center in Surat Thani Province, said that 
analyses of water samples taken from the Tapi River in 1990 
showed that the water in the river was suitable for consumption. 
But the water first had to be treated to kill the bacteria and 
improve the quality of the water as usual. Also, the water could 
be used for piscicultural activities and for water sports. 
  But water samples taken during the period 1991-1993 have 
shown that the quality of the water in the Tapi River has 
declined to dangerous levels. Today, the river is suitable for 
communications only. In some sections, officials found heavy 
metals such as lead and chromium. For example, at the Tha Thong 
dock, the lead level was 0.16 milligrams per liter, and the 
chromium level was 0.34 milligrams per liter. At the municipal 
dock, the lead level was 0.06 milligrams per liter, and the 
chromium level was 0.14 milligrams per liter. Even though these 
metals were not found everywhere along the river and even though 
the amounts found were small, this could pose a danger. If more 
and more such metals are released into the river, the river will 
become polluted, and this will destroy the ecological system. 
  Mr. Sombat said that the reason why the Tapi River is 
becoming more and more polluted is that the people who live 
along the banks of the river throw their garbage into the river, 
farmers are using pesticides, and some industrial factories are 
secretly releasing untreated waste water into the river. Besides 
this, waste materials from auto repair shops and from battery 
plants also drain into the river. Another reason is that there 
has been a lack of urban planning concerning treating waste 
water before it is released. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

