<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cesium-137 Levels for Russia, Belarus, Ukraine Detailed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0112103293 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0100 
GMT 1 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD0112103293 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By BELINFORM correspondent Lidiya Peresypkina -- TASS] </F>
  [Text] Minsk, Dec 1 -- Specialists have spent three years 
working on an updated and amplified chart of cesium-137 
contamination of territory in the states of the former Union. 
The new chart synthesizes and summarizes data obtained from 
gamma-spectrometric analysis of numerous soil samples and 
gamma-spectrometric surveys from the air. 
  ``This updated chart reflects the third post-Chernobyl 
period, which began in 1988,'' Yuriy Pokumeyko, head of the 
Belarus hydrometeorological service says. ``The radiation 
situation is now dominated by cesium-137, strontium-90 and 
plutonium-238, -239, - 240, and -241, whose half-life ranges 
from a minimum of 12 years to a maximum of almost 25,000 years. 
The breakdown, by republics, of contamination by long-life 
radionuclides with a density of one curie per square kilometre 
and above is now as follows: Belarus -- 23 percent of the 
republic's total area, Ukraine -- 5.2 percent, and Russia 0.6 
percent. The worst affected areas are Gomel, Mogilev, Zhitomir, 
Rovno, Kiev, Bryansk, Tula and Orel oblasts. I wish to point 
out that, as far as Russia is concerned, the chart has been 
augmented with information about strontium-90 contamination 
resulting from the Kyshtym accident in the Urals.'' 

</TEXT>

