<H3> <TI>   Japan To Give One Million Dollars in Aid for Chernobyl Relief </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1611204893 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1919 GMT 16 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD1611204893 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Varlamov] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo, Nov 16 TASS -- One million U.S. dollars worth 
of humanitarian aid will be rendered by Japan to Belarus to 
overcome the Chernobyl accident aftermath, in accordance with 
today's decision of the Japanese Government. 
  The first batch of the humanitarian cargo to include high- 
precision medical equipment and diagnostics instruments will be 
sent to Belarusian hospitals in mid-December. The other will be 
supplied in Minsk by February 1994. 
  According to a report of the Japanese Foreign Ministry, the 
action will be done within the framework of a 100 million dollar 
program of assistance to former Soviet republics. It was 
adopted by an international conference on assistance to new 
independent states -- 12 former soviet republics with the 
exception of the Baltic states -- in October 1992 in Tokyo. 

</TEXT>

