<H3> <TI>   Short Life Expectancy Blamed on Interference in Nature </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0112084693 Minsk ZVYAZDA in Belarusian 24 Nov 93 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> WS0112084693 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk ZVYAZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Iryna Syarohina: ``Are Sun, Air, and Water Our </F>
Enemies?''] 
  [Text] Nowadays, life expectancy in Belarus is one of the 
shortest in the world. 
  According to Academician I.I. Lishtvin, secretary of the 
Belarusian Academy of Sciences and director of the Institute for 
Ecology and Use of Natural Resources, this is connected not only 
with the aftermath of the catastrophe at the Chernobyl Nuclear 
Power Plant. We have already interfered in biological processes 
of nature to such an extent that further development of 
civilization requires special measures. Thus, for instance, 
while reclaiming a marsh, nobody thought about the harm to the 
atmosphere -- 1 hectare of marsh equalizes 5 hectares of forests 
for absorbing pollutants from the atmosphere. Purity of the 
atmosphere is an issue of great importance especially now, when 
the stream of cars used in the Republic has increased. 

</TEXT>

