<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Suggests Franco-German Sarcophagus for Chernobyl </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0212144493 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
2 Dec 93 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU0212144493 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [``me''-initialed report: ``Franco-German Sarcophagus for </F>
Chernobyl Reactor?''] 
  [Text] Wiesbaden, 1 Dec -- In the view of Federal 
Environment Minister Klaus Toepfer, of the Christian Democratic 
Union [CDU], Germany and France should, together, build a new 
sarcophagus for the disaster nuclear reactor in Chernobyl. On 
Wednesday, Toepfer said in Wiesbaden that this issue was 
discussed in the Franco-German consultations. The concrete 
coat, which was built around the reactor after the disaster in 
Ukraine, now has to be overhauled due to erosion processes. 
According to Toepfer, several pending questions (such as that 
of financing) still have to be clarified before a concrete 
decision is taken. 
  In an event organized by the Konrad-Adenauer-Foundation, 
which is close to the Christian Democratic Union [CDU], Toepfer 
predicted that the Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] 
would change its policy and support an energy consensus with the 
inclusion of nuclear energy after the Bundestag election. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

