<H5>  Summary </H5>
  1. Conclusions 
  2. Forecasts and Recommendations 
<H5>  Addendum </H5>
<H6>  Introduction </H6>

  The state of the environment in the Russian Federation in 
1992 was influenced considerably by general economic processes 
in the country. 
  These processes displayed extremely contradictory 
development 
and were influenced by the following factors: the collapse of 
the political and economic-administrative structures of the 
former USSR; the existence of long-term negative trends dating 
back to the time when the Russian economy was still part of the 
Union; the effects of new economic processes engendered by 
radical economic reform. 
  The collapse of the USSR diminished the actual chances of 
solving ecological problems on the interstate level and in 
Russia itself. The disruption of ties between republics had an 
adverse effect on the production of resource-conserving 
equipment, reagents for the treatment of waste liquids and 
gases, and other products needed for environmental protection. 
Difficulties arose in solving inter-republic ecological problems 
caused by the rising level of the Caspian Sea, the need to 
protect and reproduce the supply of water in coastal and 
trans-border aquifers, the transfer of pollutants through the 
atmosphere, and others. 
  The long-term negative tendencies with the most adverse 
effects on the state of the environment are the structural 
irregularities in the Russian economy, reflected in the 
excessive development of resource-intensive, frequently 
``dirty'' fields of production, the general technological 
underdevelopment of industry, agriculture, and construction, the 
high concentration of production units in some regions, and the 
underdeveloped infrastructure. 
  In the course of radical reform, Russia encountered new 
processes connected with the destabilization of the financial 
system, the insolvency of enterprises, and the soaring rate of 
inflation, which did much to cause the slump in production and 
investment activity. This, in turn, had a negative effect on 
conservation measures. 
  In 1992 the volume of industrial production in the national 
economy as a whole was 18.8 percent* below the 1991 figure, 
including decreases of 26.8 percent* in nonferrous metallurgy 
and 22.2 percent* in the chemical industry. The substantial 
reduction of output, however, did not result in a comparable 
reduction of environmental pollution. According to the Russian 
State Committee for Statistics, atmospheric emissions within the 
territory of Russia decreased by only 11 percent* in 1992, and 
the reduction in releases of polluted sewage was negligible. 
  Relative indicators of change in the volumes of products and 
services in different regions of the country and indicators of 
emissions and the dumping of pollutants per product cost unit 
are presented in figures 1-5. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-03A>           Figure 1. Changes in Volumes of </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-04A>           Figure 2. Atmospheric Emissions of </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-04B>           Figure 3. Changes in Total </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-05A>           Figure 4. Amount of Polluted and </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-05B>           Figure 5. Change in Dumping of </FIG>



  The reasons for this were the increased leniency in the 
oversight of technological regulations in the basic production 
units and in the operation of treatment plants, the 
deterioration of fixed assets in production, including 
resource-conserving assets, the reduction of the output and 
deterioration of the quality of chemical reagents used in the 
treatment of waste gases and liquids, and the unsatisfactory 
performance of environmental monitoring agencies. 
  The depreciation of fixed assets in industry as a whole 
exceeded 50 percent in 1992, and depreciation and the state of 
productive assets reached the critical level in several 
branches--petroleum refining, electrical power engineering, wood 
processing, and the chemical industry. This was the main reason 
why many production units in these branches became potentially 
dangerous sources of accidental environmental pollution. In 
1992, for example, the deterioration of equipment, the low 
technical standards, and the obsolescence of technological 
processes created a critical ecological situation at several 
enterprises of the pulp and paper industry, including the Bratsk 
Timber Industry Complex, the Solombalskiy Pulp and Paper 
Combine, and several other enterprises. 
  Even the meager ``remainder'' financing of environmental 
construction projects in the pre-reform years was diminished in 
1992 by the dramatic decline of investment activity throughout 
the national economy. 
  Total capital investments in environmental construction 
projects in 1992 from all funding sources were almost 20 
percent* below the 1991 figure. The volume of completed 
environmental projects was reduced dramatically. The number of 
new facilities for the decontamination of waste gases in 1992 
was almost 50 percent lower than the figure for the previous 
year. 
  Nongovernmental economic structures continued to play an 
insignificant part in the development of conservation measures, 
although the results of several interesting research and design 
projects in conservation were made available to them. There were 
no perceptible advances in the conservation, protection, and 
reproduction of natural resources in 1992. 
  To a considerable extent, this was due to the insufficient 
efforts in the past year to install a new 
economic-organizational mechanism to monitor resource use, 
particularly on the regional level. On this level, the recording 
and assessment of natural resources have not been organized 
efficiently yet, there has been virtually no progress in 
conducting a comprehensive cadastre, projects in the study and 
reproduction of resources are not being coordinated adequately, 
there are no economic controls over the use of several types of 
resources, and the main shortcoming is the lack of comprehensive 
resource management. The factors contributing to this have 
included the continuous restructuring of government 
administrative bodies, including agencies responsible for the 
management of natural resources, and the incomplete process of 
distinguishing between federal and regional ownership of natural 
resources, which has frequently resulted in the inefficient use 
of resources and the deterioration of natural complexes. 
  All of these statements are corroborated by the contents of 
the report. The purpose of the report is not a mere analysis of 
the ecological situation, however, but also the disclosure of 
the reasons for its present state and some constructive 
proposals on ways of surmounting negative tendencies. This is 
the 
purpose of the rest of this report. 
<H6>  Section 1. Environmental Quality and the State of Natural 
Resources </H6>
<H5>  1.1. Climatic Distinctions of the Year </H5>
  The global warming observed in the northern hemisphere 
reached record levels in 1990 and then decreased in the next two 
years. The average annual air temperature anomaly (in relation 
to the base period of 1951-1980) in the northern hemisphere 
dropped from 0.55 C in 1990 to 0.11 C in 1992 (Figure 
1.1.1). Meanwhile, the average monthly temperature in the 
northern hemisphere was below the norm from July to November. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-06A>           Figure 1.1.1. Regional Mean Anomalies </FIG>



  In the last five years (1988-1992), the average annual 
temperature for Russia as a whole and for the majority of its 
regions (Figure 1.1.2) exceeded the norm (by 1.4 C in 1990, 
the warmest year). The average annual temperature anomaly for 
the Russian Federation dropped from 1.4 C in 1990 to 
0.2 C in 1992. In 1992 air temperature was substantially 
lower in many parts of the country, especially West Siberia and 
the Northeast. The drop in the average annual temperature was 
not as dramatic in Central Asia, Siberia, the cis-Amur and 
Maritime region, and the cis-Baykal and Transbaykal region 
(Figure 1.1.3). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-07A>           Figure 1.1.2. Regional Mean Anomalies </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-08A>           Figure 1.1.3. Regional Mean Anomalies </FIG>



  The winter of 1992 was extraordinarily warm in general, the 
spring was also warm in most regions, air temperature in summer 
was close to the norm, and in fall it was lower than usual 
(figures 1.1.4 and 1.1.5). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-09A>           Figure 1.1.4. Average Monthly Air </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-09B>           Figure 1.1.5. Average Monthly Air </FIG>



  Atmospheric precipitation in the Russian Federation and its 
separate regions has been fairly stable in the last 100 years 
(1891-1992): Long-term deviations have been virtually absent in 
annual precipitation and winter and summer precipitation figures. 
  Humidity readings in 1992 were close to the norm in Russia, 
although they did cover a broad range. There was not a single 
case of underprecipitation in the average regional figures and 
there was only one case of excess precipitation, but the eastern 
regions (the cis-Amur and Maritime zone and the Northeast) were 
more likely to experience lighter precipitation, and rainfall 
within the European territory of Russia (ETR) was three times 
the norm. 
<H5>  [No 20, 1993 pp 4-7] </H5>
  Winter rainfall in the cis-Amur and Maritime zone was 15-20 
percent below the norm, and the deficiency of precipitation was 
particularly acute in the Northeast, where it was equivalent to 
almost 70 percent of the norm. Precipitation in the Central and 
Central Chernozem regions, in the Urals, in the south of West 
Siberia, in the south of Krasnoyarsk Kray, in the cis-Baykal and 
Transbaykal zone, and in the south of Amur Oblast was 60-80 
percent below the norm in March, and the figure in the Volga 
lowlands was 6-30 percent, and then in April this was replaced 
by excess moisture equivalent to as much as 120-160 percent of 
the norm, followed by another decrease in May, equivalent to 
60-80 percent of the norm. Monthly atmospheric precipitation 
anomalies in the summer are illustrated in Figure 1.1.6. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-10A>           Figure 1.1.6. Monthly Atmospheric </FIG>



  The distribution of the snow cover on Russian territory in 
spring 1992 deviated substantially from the norm. Conditions 
were particularly divergent in the country's European territory: 
There was very little snowfall (30-50 percent of the norm) in 
the western and southwestern regions, and snowfall figures 
exceeded the norm by 20-60 percent in the northern, eastern, and 
southeastern regions of this territory. 
  The hydrological patterns of rivers and ice conditions were 
irregular and anomalous in 1992. 
  The ice on the Don, the upper reaches of the Volga, and most 
of the rivers in the Volga basin melted 10-20 days earlier than 
usual. The Volga reservoirs were released from the ice early. 
The beginning of the spring ice flow into rivers of the Amur 
basin was exceptionally early. The ice flow began 6-10 days late 
in the upper reaches of the Pechora, Kama, and Lena and the 
middle and lower reaches of the Ob and Irtysh. 
  The high water mark in spring on the rivers of the Don basin 
hit a record low, and the water level in the upper reaches of 
the Volga, the Oka, the rivers of the Tobol basin, and the 
Kolyma was lower than usual. The water level of the Yenisey in 
spring was higher than usual, and it was close to the norm in 
Russia's other rivers. 
  Ice appeared on the Pechora, Northern Dvina, northern 
tributaries of the Volga, and lower reaches of the Yenisey 7-16 
days earlier than usual. Floating ice was seen later than usual 
in the Don and the Volga lowlands, and ice covered the Tsimlyan, 
Saratov, and Volgograd reservoirs later than usual. 
  Ice conditions differed in the non-Arctic seas in the winter 
of 1992-93. Ice formed early on the White Sea. Ice was light in 
the Baltic and Black seas. Conditions were close to the norm in 
the Caspian and Bering seas and the Sea of Japan and lighter 
than the norm in the Sea of Okhotsk. 
  There were 195 extraordinary hydrometeorological events in 
the Russian Federation in 1992, exceeding the average for the 
last seven years. Around half were accompanied by environmental 
damage and economic losses. The temperature frequently rose 
above 30 degrees. The year was distinguished by a well-defined 
summer, light frosts in spring and fall, and snowfall and storms 
in winter. 
<H5>  1.2. Air Quality and Protection </H5>
  Total emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere in 1992 
from stationary sources within the territory of Russia amounted 
to 28.2 million* tonnes, as compared to 31.8 million* in 1991. 
The reduction of 3.6 million* tonnes was mainly due to the 
pervasive slump in industrial production, particularly in the 
extractive and resource-processing branches. The relative 
stability of the extraction and use of gas (an ecologically 
clean fuel) played a positive role under these conditions. 
  Vehicle emissions totaled 22 million tonnes and exceeded the 
1991 figure. The dynamics of emissions of pollutants into the 
atmosphere, based on statistical data, are illustrated in Figure 
1.2.1. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-11A>           Figure 1.2.1. Dynamics of Atmospheric </FIG>



  These data do not include atmospheric emissions produced by 
the operation of road-construction and agricultural equipment, 
air, rail, sea, and river transport, animal husbandry complexes, 
space heaters, fires in garbage dumps and waste disposal sites, 
dust from quarries and other pollution-producing sites, forest 
fires, etc. 
  Figure 1.2.2 illustrates gross emissions of harmful 
substances from stationary sources in the country's economic 
regions in 1992. The strongest anthropogenic influences have 
been recorded in the oblasts making up the Ural economic region 
and the West Siberian, East Siberian, Northern, and Central 
economic zones. An analysis of the situation indicates that air 
pollution is comparatively uniform in the central part of 
Russia, where enterprises of almost all branches of industry are 
located. The amount and nature of air pollution in the eastern 
regions are connected with the presence of large enterprises of 
the metallurgical, gas, and petrochemical branches of industry. 
Emissions from the oil and gas complex that took shape over 
recent decades in Tyumen Oblast are still the main source of 
pollution in the West Siberian economic region and account for 
almost half of all the emissions of enterprises in that region. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-11B>           Figure 1.2.2. Distribution of Gross </FIG>



  Stricter government control revealed previously unrecorded 
sources of pollution and clarified the amount of pollutants 
emitted by previously known sources. This clarification is the 
reason for the higher emission figures in several oblasts and 
republics, including Udmurtia, Khakassia, and Tomsk Oblast. 
  The largest quantities of pollutants entered the atmosphere 
from enterprises of the fuel and energy complex, the 
metallurgical industry, and the petrochemical industry. Figure 
1.2.3 illustrates the distribution of the main elements of 
pollution in the total emissions of all recorded sources. In 
addition to producing the substances listed in the figures, 
enterprises of ferrous and nonferrous metallurgy are the main 
sources of copper oxide (90 percent of national emissions), 
cadmium, metallic nickel, hydrogen cyanide, naphthalene, and 
more than 80 percent of emissions containing sulfuric acid, 
fluorides, arsenic, and other substances. Enterprises of the 
chemical and petrochemical industry are the source of 99 percent 
of all carbon disulfide emissions, and 99.8 percent of the 
methyl mercaptan in the atmosphere comes from enterprises of the 
timber industry. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-12A>           Figure 1.2.3. Contribution of Various </FIG>



  The reduction of aircraft emissions has become a primary 
objective in recent years because these now represent almost 44 
percent of total emissions and have displayed a clear tendency 
toward increase. 
  Aircraft emissions exceed 80 percent of gross emissions in 
Krasnodar Kray, Voronezh and Tambov oblasts, the 
Kabardino-Balkar Republic, and the Republic of Mari El. 
Emissions from air transport in Omsk, Krasnodar, Ufa, Tyumen, 
Samara, Nizhniy Novgorod, Voronezh, Volgograd, and Yekaterinburg 
amounted to 100,000-150,000 tonnes in 1991. The highest levels 
were recorded in Moscow (586,200 tonnes), St. Petersburg 
(226,600 tonnes), and Novosibirsk (206,900 tonnes). Air 
transport is responsible for 77-97 percent of the air pollution 
in resort zones like Anapa, Yessentuki, Sochi, and Kislovodsk. 
  According to observations of agencies of the Russian Federal 
Hydrometeorological and Environmental Monitoring Service, the 
1992 average concentrations of one or several pollutants 
exceeded the MAC [maximum allowable concentration] in the air of 
171 cities and was equivalent to 5 times the MAC in 55 cities. 
In 83 cities single incidents of concentrations of certain 
pollutants exceeded public health standards by 10 times, and in 
nine cities the concentration was 50 times the norm. Bratsk, 
Berezniki, Kemerovo, Magnitogorsk, Moscow, Novokuznetsk, Omsk, 
Usolye-Sibirskoye, and other cities are on the list of cities 
with the heaviest air pollution every year. Pollution exceeding 
the maximum and average daily MAC was recorded in 337 cities in 
1992. High levels of air pollution are regularly recorded in the 
following cities: 
  Arkhangelsk, Amursk, Bratsk, Baykalsk, Novodvinsk, and 
Ust-Ilimsk--by methyl mercaptan; 
  Gubakha--by hydrogen sulfide; 
  Volsk--by acetaldehyde; 
  Magnitogorsk--by styrene; 
  Nizhniy Tagil, Chelyabinsk, and Yekaterinburg--by benzpyrene 
(BP); 
  Usolye-Sibirskoye--by mercury; 
  Rudnaya Pristan--by lead; 
  Norilsk--by sulfur dioxide; 
  Omsk--by ethylbenzene; 
  Berezniki, Baykalsk, Balakovo, and Kemerovo--by carbon 
disulfide; 
  Khabarovsk--by formaldehyde; 
  Gubakha and Moscow--by phenol; 
  Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk, Aleksandrovsk-Sakhalinskiy, and 
Korsakov--by soot; 
  Moscow--by carbon monoxide. 
  Air quality observations in 1988-1992 have recorded the 
reduction of average concentrations of suspended matter, soluble 
sulfates, ammonium, benzpyrene, soot, hydrogen sulfide, and 
formaldehyde as a result of cuts in production and the closure 
of enterprises. Meanwhile, there have been higher average 
concentrations of nitrogen dioxide, carbon monoxide, carbon 
disulfide, phenol, and hydrogen fluoride because of the 
irregular operations of enterprises. Higher concentrations of 
carbon monoxide, nitrogen dioxide, and formaldehyde have also 
been recorded on highways in big cities and adjacent 
territories. The highest air pollution index (API exceeding 14) 
in 1992 was recorded in the following 44 cities: Abakan, 
Angarsk, Arkhangelsk, Achinsk, Berezniki, Bratsk, Vladivostok, 
Volzhskiy, Groznyy, Gubakha, Yekaterinburg, Zima, Irkutsk, 
Kamensk-Uralskiy, Kemerovo, Krasnodar, Krasnoyarsk, Kurgan, 
Lipetsk, Magadan, Magnitogorsk, Moscow, Nizhniy Tagil, 
Novodvinsk, Novokuznetsk, Novosibirsk, Novocherkassk, Omsk, 
Petropavlovsk-Kamchatskiy, Rostov-on-Don, Saratov, Selenginsk, 
Stavropol, Taganrog, Tolyatti, Ulan-Ude, Ulyanovsk, 
Usolye-Sibirskoye, Khabarovsk, Chelyabinsk, Cherepovets, Chita, 
Shelekhov, and Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk. 
<H5>  Air Pollution Readings in Russia </H5>
  The atmospheric precipitate of chemical compounds in Russia 
can be judged from the observations of stations monitoring the 
pollution of the snow cover. The density of the observation 
network in the ETR and the Urals is one station for every 8,000 
square kilometers, and in the Asian territory of Russia (ATR) it 
is one station for every 30,000 square kilometers. The volume 
and intensity of sulfur and nitrogen precipitate in the country 
in 1992 are presented in Table 1.2.1. 


