  The acid content of winter rainfall in the Russian 
Federation 
was negligible. The pH value of the snow pack in most of this 
territory, including urbanized and agricultural regions, ranged 
from 5.5 to 5.7. A higher acid number (pH 4.5-5.5) was recorded 
in winter rains on the Kola peninsula, in the north of the ETR, 
on the eastern slopes of the Urals, and in the west of Taymyr 
and the environs of Lake Baykal and Novosibirsk. 
  The average annual intensity of metal precipitate found in 
snow samples is listed in Table 1.2.2. An analysis of the 
samples indicated that 85-95 percent of all the detected metals 
were in aerosol form and the rest was liquid filtrate. Excessive 
concentrations of metals in precipitation were recorded in areas 
measuring hundreds of square kilometers (and more rarely in 
thousands). Anomalous areas of metal concentration (tens of 
thousands of square kilometers) were located in the large 
industrial centers of the Urals, the central part of the ETR, 
and the Kuzbass. 


