------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Manganese                |                         |3.0-9.0                  | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  Changes in the lead content of precipitation during the year 
usually correspond to its content in the air (more in winter 
than in the warm season). 
  The overall mineral content of precipitation ranged from 5 
to 
25 mg/liter. The acid type of precipitation was recorded at most 
of the stations in the ETR. Fluctuations in pH values over many 
years display no distinct tendencies and are due to the natural 
variability of processes. There was more acid rain in winter 
than in summer at 64 percent of the stations, because fuel use 
patterns change in winter, tending toward the use of more liquid 
and solid types of fuel with acid-forming components--sulfur and 
nitrogen. Acid rains with a pH value of 3.5 were recorded in 
several background regions on the Valday ridge and in the 
Oka-Terrace biosphere preserve. Precipitation is more alkaline 
as it moves eastward. 
<H5>  The Earth's Ozone Layer </H5>
  Statistical processing of the data of observations in the 
network of ground stations for the measurement of the total 
ozone content (TOC) with Dobson instruments, the M-83/124, and 
the TOMS satellite system indicated a lower TOC both in winter 
and in the spring and summer months in the northern and southern 
hemispheres, with the exception of the tropics. 
  According to satellite observations, the reduction of TOC at 
an altitude of 40 kilometers, which is most vulnerable to the 
influence of the chlorine cycle, was no more than 5 percent 
during the decade, which is approximately half as high as the 
prediction based on simulation models. 
  In general, the winter of 1991-92 was one of the most 
anomalous in the whole period of ozonometric observations. The 
greatest average monthly deviations of TOC were 20 percent in 
January, 15 percent in February, and 20 percent in March. A 
lower TOC began to be recorded over North Asia and Canada in 
February 1992, and the TOC in virtually the whole 45-70 north 
latitude zone was 10-20 percent below the norm in February and 
March. 
  The period from April through August 1992 was also marked by 
a lower TOC figure in virtually all of the territory of the 
former USSR. The greatest deviations from average monthly 
figures (up to 15 percent in April and up to 10 percent in 
May-July) were recorded over the northern ETR, East Siberia, and 
Yakutia. The TOC in August was close to climatic norms. 
  Fall was marked by a somewhat lower TOC, but within the 
range 
of natural variations. 
  Although a lower ozone content over Antarctica was recorded 
last year, this is the fourth year in a row (1989-1992) that the 
``ozone hole'' was as deep and as wide as it was in 1987. The 
absence of quasi-biennial cyclical changes was apparently due to 
the prevailing influence of chemical destruction in comparison 
with dynamic fluctuations. The maximum area with a TOC below 200 
Dobson units was recorded on 27 September 1992 and is estimated 
at 22.6 million square kilometers. 
<H5>  1.3. Water Resources and Their Quality, Protection, and Use </H5>
<H5>  Surface Water </H5>
  The combined flow of all of the rivers in Russia in 1992 was 
5 percent above the average. Regional changes in the flow are 
illustrated in Figure 1.3.1. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-17A>           Figure 1.3.1. Regional Changes in </FIG>



  There was less water in the rivers than in 1991 in almost 
all 
parts of the ETR, with the exception of the north. This tendency 
was apparently connected with the onset of a drought in vast 
areas of the ETR, which could complicate environmental 
conditions and compound the water shortage in the central and 
southern regions. 
  The water level in the Volga River in 1992 was lower than in 
1991 and was almost equivalent to the average. The levels of the 
Don, Dnieper, Ob, and Angara rivers were below the norm. 
  Particularly high water levels were recorded in the rivers 
of 
Karelia and the Kola peninsula (5-20 percent above the norm) and 
rivers in East Siberia (5-11 percent above the norm). The level 
was close to the norm or 1-15 percent below in the rivers of the 
Central Chernozem, North Caucasus, Ural, Volga, and Far Eastern 
economic regions. 
  The reduced flow in the large Russian rivers used 
extensively 
in economic operations now ranges from 10 percent below the norm 
for the Volga River to 15-40 percent for the Don, Kuban, Terek, 
and other rivers. 
  The degradation of small Russian rivers was compounded by 
the 
erosion in drainage areas. In 1992 these processes were most 
intense in the Central, Volga-Vyatka, cis-Volga, West Siberian, 
and East Siberian regions. 
  The amounts of river water used for the regulation of 
supplies in reservoirs were significant: 3.96 km[.sup]3[/] 
removed from the Don River and 0.6 km[.sup]3[/] from the 
Kuban River for accumulation in the Tsimlyanskoye Reservoir, 1.6 
km[.sup]3[/] from the Yenisey River for the replenishment of 
supplies in the Krasnoyarsk Reservoir, and around 0.9 
km[.sup]3[/] from the Volga for the replenishment of water 
reserves in all reservoirs. 
<H5>  Water Use and the Dumping of Polluted Sewage </H5>
  According to state water use records, the total amount of 
water taken out of natural bodies of water in 1992 was 6.3* 
km[.sup]3[/] below the 1991 figure and amounted to 110.7* 
km[.sup]3[/]. The reasons were the slump in production and 
the reduced output of electrical power. The total included 94.4* 
km[.sup]3[/] of fresh water and 5.2* km[.sup]3[/] of sea 
water, and 8.5* km[.sup]3[/] were used for the inter-basin 
and territorial redistribution of supplies. The amount used for 
national economic needs was 90* km[.sup]3[/], including 48.5* 
km[.sup]3[/] for industrial needs, 15.4* km[.sup]3[/] for 
irrigation, 14.7* km[.sup]3[/] for drinking and household 
needs, 4* km[.sup]3[/] for agriculture, and 7.4* 
km[.sup]3[/] for other needs. 
  Changes in water use in 1992 in different regions of the 
Russian Federation in relation to 1991 figures are illustrated 
in Figure 1.3.2. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-17B>           Figure 1.3.2. Changes in Water Use in </FIG>



  In industry, 22 percent* of all of the water used came from 
natural bodies of water, and 78 percent* was recycled (76 
percent* in 1991). The dynamics of water use are presented in 
Figure 1.3.3, and the data on recycled water use are presented 
in Figure 1.3.4. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-18A>           Figure 1.3.3. Dynamics of Water </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-18B>           Figure 1.3.4. Dynamics of Water </FIG>



  Losses of water in transport amounted to 8.4* km[.sup]3[/]. 
  The amount of sewage released into bodies of water in 1992 
was 2.6* km[.sup]3[/] less than in 1991 and totaled 70.6* 
km[.sup]3[/], with 38 percent (27.1* km[.sup]3[/]) falling 
into the category of polluted sewage (untreated or partially 
decontaminated). 
<H5>  [No 21, 1993 pp 4-7] </H5>
  Most of the polluted sewage was dumped by enterprises in 
industry (41.7 percent*) and by public utilities (44.3 
percent*). Polluted sewage dumping in different regions of the 
country and changes in the amounts in 1992 in relation to 1991 
figures are presented in figures 1.3.5 and 1.3.6, and the 
distribution of polluted sewage among the basins of the main 
Russian rivers is illustrated in Figure 1.3.7. The amount of 
polluted sewage dumped in the last six years (in cubic 
kilometers) was 16.7* in 1987, 23.3* in 1988, 27.1* in 1989, 
27.8* in 1990, 28.0* in 1991, and 27.1* in 1992. In the last 
four years the amount of polluted sewage has remained virtually 
the same. The total amount of adequately treated sewage in 1992 
was 2.8* km[.sup]3[/], or 9 percent* of all the sewage 
requiring treatment (30* km[.sup]3[/]). This occurred because 
treatment plants are overloaded and inefficient. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-19A>           Figure 1.3.5. Polluted Sewage Dumped </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-19B>           Figure 1.3.6. Changes in Quantities </FIG>





<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-20A>           Figure 1.3.7. Polluted Sewage Dumped </FIG>



  The amount of water in sewer drains was 2.2* km[.sup]3[/] 
greater than in 1991. 
  The following were dumped into bodies of water along with 
sewage in 1992 (in thousands of tonnes): 
  petroleum products--39.4* 
  suspended matter--1,089.9* 
  common phosphorus--59.8* 
  ammonium nitrogen--187.0* 
  phenols--0.2* 
  synthetic surfactants--8.9* 
  copper compounds--0.9* 
  ferrous compounds--51.2* 
  zinc compounds--1.6* 
  The amount of petroleum products dumped with sewage was 
considerably larger than in 1991. 
<H5>  Surface Water Pollution </H5>
  The quality of water in the majority of bodies of water does 
not meet standard requirements. Observations of surface water 
quality over many years have revealed a tendency toward an 
increase in the number of sites with high pollution levels (over 
10 times the MAC) and extremely high levels (over 100 times the 
MAC). 
  The state of sources of water (surface and subterranean) and 
centralized water supply systems cannot guarantee the required 
quality of drinking water, and in some regions (the Volga 
lowlands, the southern Urals, the Kuzbass, and some northern 
territories) this is jeopardizing human health. 
  Sanitary and epidemiological oversight agencies regularly 
announce high levels of surface water pollution. Their data on 
the sanitary condition of surface water in the locations of 
drinking water supplies are presented in Table 1.3.1. Around a 
third of all the pollutants enter sources of water in rainfall 
and surface runoff from the territories of populated communities 
with unsatisfactory sanitation and of agricultural facilities 
and fields, causing the seasonal deterioration of the quality of 
drinking water that is recorded each year in big cities, 
including Moscow, during the spring rains. This results in the 
excessive chlorination of drinking water, and this is also 
dangerous to human health because of the formation of 
organochlorine compounds. 


Table 1.3.1. Sanitary Condition of Sources of Drinking Water Supplies 
(percentage of analyzed samples not meeting hygienic requirements) 

Indicators                   1980            1991            1992 

Sanitary-chemical            15.4            30.2            29.4 

Microbiological              22.9            24.4            27.16 

lactose-positive             --              85.4            92.9 
Escherichia coli 

coliphage                    --              --              9.16 

infectious pathogens         --              3.1             2.44 

helminthoma pathogens        --              1.2             3.31 


  The quality of the public supply of drinking water in 1992 
was virtually the same as in 1991: 22.1 percent of the analyzed 
samples did not meet the sanitary-chemical requirements of 
hygienic standards, and 12.3 percent did not satisfy 
microbiological requirements. 
  The drinking water of around a third of the population comes 
from decentralized sources. An analysis of the water in these 
sources indicated that 28 percent of the samples did not satisfy 
the sanitary-chemical requirements and 29.4 percent did not 
satisfy the bacteriological requirements of hygienic standards. 
In general, the drinking water of around 50 percent of the 
population of the Russian Federation still does not satisfy 
certain quality indicators. The situation is particularly 
serious in Arkhangelsk, Kursk, Tomsk, Yaroslavl, Kaluga, and 
Kaliningrad oblasts, Maritime Kray, Kalmykia, Dagestan, and 
Karachay-Cherkessia. 
  It is disturbing that 21.7 percent of the public utilities 
and 20.1 percent of the departmental water systems had to pipe 
water to the public in 1992 without decontaminating it because 
of the lack of special installations. This creates favorable 
conditions for epidemics. 
  From 31 to 64 percent of the sources of drinking water in 
Kaluga, Smolensk, Kursk, Saratov, Kaliningrad, and Chita oblasts 
have no sanitary protective zones. 
  The results of analyses of samples of drinking water from 
public water supplies are presented in Table 1.3.2. 


Table 1.3.2. Sanitary Condition of Drinking Water from Public Network in 
1990-92 (percentage of analyzed samples not meeting hygienic requirements) 

Indicators                    1990             1991             1992 

Sanitary-chemical             22.5             23.8             22.1 

Microbiological               12.5             12.8             12.3 


  The unsatisfactory sanitary and chemical state of water 
supply lines and networks leads to the secondary pollution of 
drinking water on its way to the consumer, primarily as a result 
of accidents, which have caused outbreaks of infectious 
diseases. The number of these diseases increased from 9 in 1991 
to 16 in 1992, and the total number of victims was 2,457. Cases 
of infection were recorded in Uglich in Yaroslavl Oblast, in 
Pinega in Arkhangelsk Oblast, in Konakovo in Tver Oblast, and in 
Kiselevsk in Kemerovo Oblast. 
  The state of water supply lines in public recreation areas 
is 
unsatisfactory (Table 1.3.3). 


Table 1.3.3. Sanitary Condition of Bodies of Water in Public Recreation Areas 
(percentage of analyzed samples not meeting hygienic requirements) 

Indicators                         1991                   1992 

Sanitary-chemical                  31.5                   32.9 

Microbiological                    24.6                   21.12 

lactose-positive E-coli            88.3                   87.9 

infectious pathogens               5.0                    5.34 

coliphage                          --                     7.34 

helminthoma pathogens              0.7                    1.82 


  The details of water use, sewage dumping, and surface water 
quality in the basins of the main rivers and lakes in Russia are 
presented below. 
  The Neva River basin: The provision of industry, 
agriculture, and the population with water is no problem from 
the standpoint of quantity--this requires no more than 1 percent 
of the average annual flow. 
  Releases of polluted sewage, however, have increased each 
year. In 1992, 710,000 tonnes of pollutants were dumped in 
bodies of water in the Neva basin. None of the sewage in this 
basin has been treated adequately. 
  In 1992, 1.5* km[.sup]3[/] of industrial, agricultural, 
and municipal sewage, including 0.35* km[.sup]3[/] of 
polluted sewage, were dumped in Lake Ladoga. In 
addition to the serious pollution in coastal regions, there is 
the severe pollution of Volkhov Cove and the year-round shipping 
lanes in the northern part of the lake. As a result of biogenic 
substances from agricultural lands and facilities, which enter 
the lake mainly in surface runoff, there are signs of 
eutrophication in many parts of the lake. 
  The Dnieper River basin: The upper reaches of the 
river are located in Russia. The amount of fresh water removed 
from this basin in 1992 was 1.07* km[.sup]3[/], and the 
amount used was 1.03 km[.sup]3[/]. 
  The region is distinguished by a high recycling rate--95 
percent* of the water supply. The amount of sewage dumped in the 
river is 0.6* km[.sup]3[/], including 0.3* km[.sup]3[/] of 
polluted sewage. Waste treatment plants can handle 0.5 
km[.sup]3[/], exceeding the amount requiring treatment. The 
quality rating of the water in the Dnieper and Desna rivers in 
Russia ranges from ``clean'' to ``polluted.'' 
  The Don River basin: The amount taken out of the 
river for use is 9.8* km[.sup]3[/] (around 42 percent of the 
average annual flow). Water shortages in the region can be acute 
because up to 50 percent of the water is used during the dry 
season (June-September). 
  In the upper reaches of the river, the section near Donskoy 
is the most highly polluted with nitrogen compounds (up to 10 
times the MAC). The quality of water in the Don lowlands has 
been stabilized, although it is still distinguished by an 
excessive average annual content of nitrites and petroleum 
products (up to six times the MAC) and copper compounds (up to 
eight times the MAC). 
  The water in the Russian part of the Northern Donets River 
is 
rated ``polluted.'' The content of petroleum products, phenols, 
zinc and copper compounds, and other pollutants can be as high 
as 3.5-7 times the MAC in the small rivers of the Don River 
basin. 
  The Kuban River basin: This is one of the regions 
with limited water resources. The amount used each year exceeds 
10* km[.sup]3[/], or 74 percent of the average annual flow. 
More than 1* km[.sup]3[/] is lost during transport. 
  In 1992, 1.8* km[.sup]3[/] of polluted sewage, containing 
677,000 tonnes of pollutants, was dumped in the Kuban River 
basin. The result is a high level of pollution in several of its 
tributaries and sections of the river near Nevinnomyssk and 
Armavir. 
  There is a higher content of copper and ferrous compounds in 
the upper reaches of tributaries of the Kuban, particularly the 
Uryup River, due to the sewage of ore-dressing combines. An 
excessive nitrite content (up to five times the MAC) was 
recorded in the Kuban River from Karachayevsk to the Krasnodar 
Reservoir. The water in the Krasnodar Reservoir is rated 
``moderately polluted.'' Organic chlorine and phosphorus 
pesticides and 2,4-D-aminosalicylate have been found in this 
water. Pipeline accidents raised the content of petroleum 
products up to 27 times the MAC in the Kuban River near Temryuk. 
  Meanwhile, the content of organic chlorine and phosphorous 
pesticides in the Kuban River delta decreased because of the 
reduced use of these pesticides in agricultural areas of the 
river lowlands in 1992. 
  The Volga River basin: In 1992, 37.3* 
km[.sup]3[/] of fresh water was removed from bodies of water 
here, representing 34 percent* of all the water collected in 
Russia and 14 percent of the annual flow in the river basin. The 
amount of sewage dumped in surface bodies of water here was 22* 
km[.sup]3[/], including 10.7* km[.sup]3[/] of polluted 
sewage. The amount of polluted sewage released in the Volga 
basin represented 39 percent* of all the polluted sewage in 
Russia. 
  The water in the Volga series of reservoirs has high 
concentrations of phenol (2-5 times the MAC), petroleum products 
(3-10 times the MAC), and copper compounds (5-6 times the MAC). 
Nitrogen compounds, methanol, cyanide, and zinc were found in 
the water below Nizhniy Novgorod. 
  The average annual content of ammonium and nitrite nitrogen 
in the Oka River was 2-9 times the MAC, and the content of 
petroleum products was 4-14 times the MAC. The level of water 
pollution by ammonium nitrogen has been stabilized at 6-12 times 
the MAC in the Moscow and Pakhra rivers. Water quality displayed 
serious deterioration in the Klyazma River (near Kovrov) in 
1992, with the average annual content of petroleum products 
recorded at 38 times the MAC within the city limits and 100 
times the MAC downstream from the city. 
  The level of pollution by organochlorine pesticides has been 
too high for several years in the Chapayevka River (in 
Chapayevsk). The water in the Chusovaya River (in Pervouralsk) 
always has excessive levels of copper compounds (57-101 times 
the MAC), zinc (more than 10 times the MAC), and chromium (up to 
20 times the MAC). 
  The Ural River basin: Given the present level of 
water consumption, this is one of the regions with a water 
shortage. Water intake in the basin within Russian territory in 
1992 was 2.9* km[.sup]3[/], representing 35 percent of the 
average flow and equivalent to all of the river flow in dry 
years. Around 2.2* km[.sup]3[/] of sewage, including 0.2* 
km[.sup]3[/] of polluted sewage, was dumped in surface bodies 
of water in the basin during the year. There was a particularly 
perceptible increase in the amount of ferrous and nitrogen 
compounds dumped in this basin. Excessive concentrations of 
ammonium and nitrite nitrogen, sulfates, chlorides, ferrous 
compounds, and petroleum products have been recorded in the 
water of the Ural River. The most heavily polluted sections of 
the river are near Orsk and Orenburg. The water downstream from 
the sewage drain of the Orsk-Khalilovsk Metallurgical Combine is 
always distinguished by excessive concentrations of petroleum 
products (up to 33 times the MAC) and sporadic high readings of 
phenol (up to 200 times the MAC). The Ilek River, a tributary of 
the Ural, is polluted by hexavalent chromium as a result of 
underground seepage from the storage tanks of plants in 
Aktyubinsk (Kazakhstan). 
  The Terek River basin: Water conditions are 
critical here. Water intake in 1992 amounted to 6.5* 
km[.sup]3[/], or 59.6 percent* of the average annual flow. 
Around 2* km[.sup]3[/] are lost in irrigation supply lines. 
Around 0.6* km[.sup]3[/] of sewage, including 0.4* 
km[.sup]3[/] of polluted sewage, is dumped into surface 
bodies of water in the basin. The Terek River and its 
tributaries are polluted by ferrous compounds, zinc, ammonium 
nitrogen, and petroleum products, and in terms of degrees of 
pollution the water is rated ``moderately polluted'' and 
``polluted.'' 
  The Pechora River basin: Water intake in 1992 was 
0.57* km[.sup]3[/], or 0.3 percent of the average annual flow. 
  The amount of sewage released into bodies of water in the 
basin in 1992 was 0.48* km[.sup]3[/], including 0.05* 
km[.sup]3[/] of polluted sewage. The main sources of 
pollution in the rivers of this basin are enterprises of the 
oil, gas, and coal industries and geological prospecting 
organizations. 
  Excessive concentrations of phenol, petroleum products, and 
copper compounds have been recorded all along the river, with 
the highest content, of up to 8-20 times the MAC, near Pechora 
and Vuktyl. 
  The Northern Dvina River basin: Water intake in 
1992 was 1.2* km[.sup]3[/], 81 percent* of which was used for 
industrial purposes. Around 1.0* km[.sup]3[/] of sewage, 
including 0.8* km[.sup]3[/] of polluted sewage, containing 
1.5 million tonnes of pollutants, was released into the basin. 
  Petroleum products, copper, nitrogen compounds, and certain 
substances characteristic of the sewage of the pulp and paper 
industry--lignosulfanates, formaldehyde, and methanol--are still 
the most prevalent pollutants in the water of the Northern Dvina 
River. 
  Chronically high levels of water pollution are 
characteristic 
of the small rivers of the Kola peninsula in the operational 
zone of the Norilskiy Nikel state concern. The highest 
concentrations of nickel compounds (38-43 times the MAC) have 
been recorded here. The most highly polluted body of water is 
still the Nyuduay River, where critical levels of several copper 
and nickel compounds were found in 1992. 
  The Ob River basin: This river is subject to 
strong anthropogenic influences from its source to its estuary. 
Around 10.5* km[.sup]3[/] of water were taken out of the Ob 
River basin in 1992 for use. Around 7.1* km[.sup]3[/] of 
sewage was dumped in surface bodies of water in the basin. Of 
the total amount, 3.8* km[.sup]3[/] of the sewage required 
treatment, 3.4* km[.sup]3[/] was treated, but only 25 percent 
met standard requirements after treatment. 
  The pollution of the water by phenols and petroleum products 
has been recorded in all sections of the Ob River. The water in 
all sections is rated ``polluted,'' and in some sections it is 
categorized as ``contaminated'' (from Surgut to Polnovat) and 
``highly contaminated'' (in Kolpashevo and Aleksandrovskoye). 
  The average annual concentration of petroleum products in 
some sections of the Irtysh River has risen as high as 56-114 
times the MAC. The water in the Irtysh River near Tobolsk and 
the Tura River near Tyumen is rated ``highly contaminated,'' and 
the water in the Tobol River near Tobolsk is categorized as 
``extremely contaminated.'' 
  The tributaries of the Tobol River are severely polluted. 
The 
highest level of contamination is in the Iset River near 
Yekaterinburg and Aramil. The Miass River (Chelyabinsk) has a 
``highly contaminated'' rating, and the Tura River (Verkhoturye 
and Turinsk) and Salda River, where the average annual content 
of copper compounds reaches 264 times the MAC, are rated 
``extremely contaminated.'' The water in the Nitsa, Neyva, 
Pyshma, Kunara, and Lyalya rivers and the section of the Tagil 
River near Verkhniy Tagil and Nizhniy Tagil is categorized as 
``contaminated'' and ``extremely contaminated.'' 
  The Yenisey River basin: The amount of water taken 
out of water sources in the Yenisey basin for economic and 
household use in 1992 was 0.6* km[.sup]3[/] less than in 1991 
and totaled 4.97* km[.sup]3[/]. Around 3.9* km[.sup]3[/] 
of sewage was dumped into surface bodies of water in the basin, 
2.34* km[.sup]3[/] required treatment, 1.33* km[.sup]3[/] 
underwent decontamination treatment, and only 1.1 percent* was 
treated adequately. Around 62 percent of all the polluted sewage 
entering the Yenisey River basin comes from the Angara River 
basin. Waste treatment plants in this region are capable of 
handling 1.4 km[.sup]3[/], but only 0.35 percent of them are 
operating efficiently. 
  The most prevalent substances polluting the water in the 
basin are petroleum products, phenols, copper compounds, zinc, 
and others. Average annual concentrations of petroleum products 
reached 13-15 times the MAC in the upper and middle reaches of 
the Yenisey, and hydrocarbons, resins, and asphaltenes were 
found in the water near Kyzyl. 
  Water pollution is more intense downstream. Whereas the 
water 
in the upper reaches of the Yenisey is rated ``contaminated,'' 
certain sections in the lowlands are categorized as ``highly 
contaminated.'' 
  Extremely high levels of methyl mercaptan and hydrogen 
sulfide (hundreds of times the MAC) and high levels of lignin, 
cyanide, rhodanine, and petroleum products have been more common 
in the Angara River in recent years. The pollution rating of the 
water in the Angara River and its tributaries ranges from 
``polluted'' to ``highly contaminated.'' 
  The Lake Baykal basin: Sewage releases in 1992 
were the same as in 1991 and amounted to 0.23* km[.sup]3[/]. 
Although the capacity of sewage treatment plants exceeds the 
quantity of polluted sewage requiring treatment, only 11 
percent* of the treated sewage satisfies standard requirements. 
  The main sources of pollution in the lake are still the 
Selenginsk TsKK [Pulp and Cardboard Combine] and Baykalsk TsBK 
[pulp and paper combine]. Almost 70 percent of their sewage 
consists of decomposition-resistant organic substances. 
  The pollutants released into the lake with the sewage of the 
Baykalsk TsBK in 1992 surpassed all recorded indicators in 1991, 
including a 37-percent increase in phenols, an increase of 19 
percent in chlorides, and an increase of 5 percent in 
oxidation-resistant organic substances. 
  The sewage dumped in the Lake Baykal basin in 1992 included 
26,000* tonnes of sulfates, 18,000* tonnes of chlorides, 1,000* 
tonnes of nitrates, 350* tonnes of synthetic surfactants, 170* 
tonnes of common phosphorus, around 1* tonne of phenol, and 
large quantities of other pollutants. 
  Concentrations of petroleum products and phenols were higher 
in all of the large tributaries of Lake Baykal in 1992, and this 
increased the content of these substances in the lake. The 
largest increases in petroleum products and sulfates were 
recorded in the southern part of the lake. 
  The Lena River basin: In 1992, just as in previous 
years, the amount of water used for economic purposes 
represented only a negligible part of available resources and 
amounted to 0.39* km[.sup]3[/], which was 2 percent* below 
the 1991 figure. Around 0.25* km[.sup]3[/] of sewage was 
released into surface bodies of water in the basin. Around 0.18* 
km[.sup]3[/] of the sewage required treatment, and 26 
percent* satisfied standard requirements after treatment. 
  Most of the rivers in the Lena River basin are categorized 
as 
``moderately polluted'' bodies of water, with an average annual 
pollutant content of no more than 5-10 times the MAC. 
  The highest phenol content (up to 17 times the MAC) in the 
Lena River is usually recorded during spring floods and is due 
to anthropogenic influences and to natural processes. The 
readings of up to 12-16 times the MAC for copper compounds are 
due to the solubility of the minerals lining the river bed and 
the partial thawing of permafrost. 
  The Kolyma River basin: The main source of the 
suspended matter, petroleum products, phenols, and ammonium 
nitrogen in the water of the Kolyma River and its tributaries is 
the sewage of Glavalmazzoloto enterprises and public utilities. 
  The highest levels of pollution in the Kolyma River and the 
other rivers of this basin are recorded during the spring 
floods, when the maximum concentration of suspended matter rises 
as high as 123-414 mg/l, the level of copper compounds is 70 
times the MAC, and the level of ammonium nitrogen is 9 times the 
MAC. 
  The Amur River basin: In spite of the relatively 
small quantities of water removed from the Amur River for 
economic and household use (1.34* km[.sup]3[/], or 0.03 
percent* of the average monthly flow), 0.88* km[.sup]3[/] of 
sewage was dumped into this basin in 1992. Around 0.65* 
km[.sup]3[/] required treatment, and only 5 percent* 
satisfied standard requirements after treatment. 
  The quality rating of the water in the Amur River changes 
from ``moderately polluted'' to ``highly contaminated'' as the 
water flow downstream. The highest levels of pollution are near 
the rural community of Bogorodskoye and the city of Nikolayevsk, 
where maximum concentrations of copper compounds reach 80 times 
the MAC, the zinc content is 56 times the MAC, and the phenol 
content is 90 times the MAC. The average level of copper 
compounds in the Kholdomi and Silinka rivers reached 21-57 times 
the MAC and the zinc content reached 21-71 times the MAC, with 
respective maximums of 250 and 120 times the MAC. 
  The Ussuri River has a ``moderately polluted'' rating, and 
sections of its tributaries are rated ``contaminated'' or 
``highly contaminated.'' 
  Phenols are the most common pollutant in the rivers of the 
Kamchatka peninsula. The content of these reaches 3-7 
times the MAC. Maximum concentrations of phenol were as high as 
20-26 times the MAC in some of these rivers during the spring 
floods of 1992. Enterprises of the woodworking industry, timber 
rafting, and the swamp waters of the West Kamchatka Plain are 
the main sources of phenols. 
  The content of other pollutants is negligible and generally 
stays within the limits of the MAC. Most of the bodies of water 
on the peninsula have a ``clean'' rating, and only a few are 
rated ``moderately polluted.'' 
  Most of the rivers of Sakhalin Island have a 
``moderately contaminated'' rating, and the average annual 
content of pollutants in the water does not exceed 4-5 times the 
MAC. The Okhinka River (in Okha) is rated ``highly 
contaminated,'' with an average annual petroleum product content 
of 26 times the MAC and a maximum content of 49 times the MAC. 
<H5>  The Seas </H5>
  All of the inland and land-locked seas in Russia are exposed 
to intense anthropogenic influences in their water and in their 
catchment basins. 
  Water pollution levels are monitored in all of the inland 
and 
land-locked seas. The degree of pollution is measured by a 
7-point scale of water quality, ranging from ``very clean'' to 
``extremely contaminated.'' 
  Quantities of sewage released into the seas of the Russian 
Federation in 1992 are presented in Table 1.3.4. 


Table 1.3.4. Quantity and Quality of Sewage Dumped in Seas 

Sea          Total,          Polluted     Standard-clean     Standard-clean 
             km[.sup]3[/]                  without            after treatment 
                                          treatment 

Baltic       6.40*           2.00*        4.40*              0.01* 

Azov         14.28*          4.27*        9.59*              0.42* 

Black        0.87*           0.41*        0.36*              0.11* 

Caspian      28.21*          11.59*       15.61*             1.01* 

White        1.61*           1.06*        0.49*              0.06* 

Barents      0.66*           0.20*        0.34*              0.12* 

Kara         11.37*          5.36*        5.12*              0.90* 

Laptev       0.26*           0.12*        0.07*              0.07* 

East         0.06*           0.017*       0.04*              0.01* 
Siberian 

Bering       0.33*           0.005*       0.28*              0.0* 

Okhotsk      1.26*           0.74*        0.48*              0.05* 

Japan        0.60*           0.29*        0.29*              0.01* 


  Processes of attrition were characteristic of coastal areas, 
and more than 60 percent of the coastline is suffering from 
destruction, erosion, and submersion. This is inflicting 
considerable damage on the national economy and is another 
source of marine pollution. 
  The Azov Sea is the most shallow and ecologically 
vulnerable of the inland seas. The development of its ecosystem 
depends on the water level of the rivers flowing into it and on 
water exchange with the Black Sea. The Azov Sea is distinguished 
by intensive shipping, a high concentration of industry, and 
high population density on the coastal strip and throughout the 
territory of its basin. 
  Most of the pollutants in the sea are carried by the runoff 
of the Don and Kuban rivers and the sewage of enterprises in 
industry, including the fish industry, public utilities, 
construction, and agriculture. 
  The level of pollution in the coastal regions of the eastern 
part of the sea remained stable from 1987 to 1991, but higher 
concentrations of pollutants were recorded in 1992, resulting in 
the deterioration of water quality in all of the monitored 
regions. Average levels of twice the MAC and maximum levels of 
5-6 times the MAC of dissolved mercury were found, just as they 
had been in 1991, on the surface of Taganrog Bay and in the Don 
River estuary. Severe mercury pollution was also recorded in 
Temryuk Bay (up to three times the MAC). Hydrometeorological 
conditions were the reason for two cases of oxygen deficiency at 
the bottom of Temryuk Bay on the shore of the Kuban River. The 
reduction of the oxygen content on the shoreline of the Kuban 
River and in its channel was measured at 6-7 percent in 1992. 
  Black Sea: The coastal waters of Krasnodar Kray 
were rated ``moderately polluted.'' The main pollutants in this 
region were petroleum hydrocarbons. The level of these had 
reached nine times the MAC in the ports of Tuapse and 
Novorossiysk in 1991. Accidents on maritime vessels were the 
main cause of this kind of pollution. 
  Caspian Sea: The water level and ecological state 
of the largest inland drainage basin depend on surface runoff, 
mainly from the Volga River, evaporation, and economic 
activities in the water and the catchment basin. The water level 
has been rising recently. In 1992 the average level was 27.04 
meters (as of 1 January 1993), displaying an average rise of 15 
centimeters. 
  A steady tendency toward higher levels of pollution in the 
Russian parts of the North Caspian was recorded from 1986 to 
1992. The rate of pollution stabilized in 1992. We can expect 
the rising water level to increase the pollution in the Volga 
River delta. The level of pollution is rising because the 
accumulated sediment in parts of the delta is releasing more 
pollutants. The water in the western part of the North Caspian 
is categorized as ``contaminated,'' and the water in other 
regions has a ``polluted'' rating, and a steady increase in 
pollution has been recorded there. 
  The improvement of ecological conditions in the North 
Caspian 
will require a broad-scale program for more efficient water use 
in the Volga River basin, which is the main source of the 
pollution. A tendency toward lower levels of pollution and the 
subsequent stabilization of this level were recorded in the 
North Caspian from 1989 to 1992, and the water there has been 
categorized as ``polluted'' for the last three years. 
  Baltic Sea: The most highly polluted regions are 
the Neva Gulf and Vyborg Cove, where the water is rated ``highly 
contaminated'' and ``contaminated.'' 
  In 1992 the average content of phenol rose to 4-7 times the 
MAC in all parts of the sea. In the Neva Gulf the concentration 
of copper reached 19 times the MAC and manganese and lead levels 
exceeded the MAC. 
  There was a tendency toward increased water pollution in 
Kursk Gulf and the eastern part of the Gulf of Finland. 
  Barents Sea: The open expanses and coastal zones 
of the sea are rated ``clean'' or ``very clean,'' with the 
exception of the Kola Inlet. There is always a thin layer of 
petroleum products on the surface of the water in the regions of 
intense shipping. The water in the White Sea is still 
basically clean. 
  Arctic seas: The vulnerability of marine 
ecosystems in the Arctic basin is due to the inadequate ability 
of the cold water to cleanse itself of pollutants carried by 
river discharge. The main sources of pollution here are the Ob, 
Yenisey, Lena, and Kolyma rivers. Most of the pollutants 
accumulate in the river estuaries. Pollutants are also carried 
along the periphery of the whole Arctic basin toward Alaska by 
circumpolar currents. 
  The sources of pollution are enterprises of nonferrous 
metallurgy, electrical power engineering, and public utilities. 
In addition, large quantities of radioactive substances have 
been submerged in the Barents and Kara seas. 
  The combined activity of the liquid radioactive waste (LRW) 
dumped in the northern seas is 24.4 kc. Most of it was dumped in 
the Barents Sea (12.844 kc) and the Kara Sea (11.5 kc). Most of 
the solid radioactive waste (SRW) submerged in the northern seas 
consisted of cold waste and medium-activity waste. Total 
activity is 40 c in the Barents Sea and over 15 kc in the Kara 
Sea. In 1992, 3,066 m[.sup]3[/] of LRW with activity of 18 c 
was dumped in the northern seas. 
  Radiation readings in the SRW burial sites (prior to 1967) 
and the LRW dump sites (prior to 1990) registered no cases of 
dangerous radioactive pollution directly in the disposal sites 
and the surrounding water. For the last 25 years, however, 
radiation levels have not been measured directly in the SRW 
disposal sites. 
  Far Eastern seas: Hydrological conditions in these 
deep seas depend on water exchange with the Pacific Ocean. 
Pollutants accumulate mainly on the continental shelf. The 
sources of pollution in the Far Eastern seas are enterprises of 
electrical power engineering, the oil and gas industry, and 
public utilities. 
  Water quality in the northern part of the Sea of Okhotsk, in 
Nagayev and Gertner bays (Tauyskaya Inlet), was rated 
``moderately polluted'' in 1991 and 1992. No tendency toward 
pollution has been observed in the open expanses of the 
Tauyskaya Inlet in the past five years. According to available 
data, there are no indications of any such tendency in the 
southwestern part of the sea (the shelf of Sakhalin Island). We 
can say without any hesitation, however, that the environs of 
the settlement of Starodubskiy are always the most critical 
site: The water there is rated ``contaminated,'' and it is 
``highly contaminated'' in the harbor. Phenol levels have risen 
to 45 times the MAC. 
  In Petr Velikiy Gulf in the Sea of Japan, the level of 
pollution has been stabilized since 1989 in Zolotoy Rog Bay and 
in Amursk and Ussuriysk gulfs, where water quality is always 
rated ``polluted'' or ``contaminated.'' The content of dissolved 
oxygen has occasionally decreased in Zolotoy Rog Bay. The most 
highly polluted part of the Tatar Strait is always the area near 
Aleksandrovka. 
<H5>  Ground Water Use and Pollution </H5>
  Exploratory projects in Russia (in 1992) revealed the 
locations of 3,196 underground sources of potable water and 
water for the production sphere and for irrigation, with 
combined reserves of 26.7 km[.sup]3[/] a year. The sources of 
around 18.2 km[.sup]3[/] a year are ready for commercial use. 
The federation average for the use of these reserves does not 
exceed 33 percent. 
  The amount of ground water used in 1992 was 11.9* 
km[.sup]3[/], 75 percent in households, 21 percent in 
production, and 4 percent in the irrigation of fields and 
pastures. 
  Subterranean sources of water (particularly in the water 
table closest to the surface) are polluted by man's economic 
activities along with the other elements of the environment. 
According to the geological organizations of Roskomnedra [RF 
State Committee for Geology and the Use of Mineral Resources], 
around 760 sites of ground water pollution have been discovered, 
and they have displayed steady levels of pollution for several 
years. They include 70 potable water intakes in Ufa, Tula, Orel, 
Tambov, Kamensk-Shakhtinskiy, and other cities where the 
deterioration of water quality has been recorded. Pollution in 
320 areas is connected with the activities of industrial 
enterprises. 
  The most common sources of ground water pollution are oil 
fields, mining enterprises, leach fields, the slurry tanks and 
scrap heaps of metallurgical plants, chemical waste and 
fertilizer storage tanks, garbage dumps, animal husbandry 
complexes, and residential communities with no sewers. Sites of 
ground water pollution now cover hundreds of square kilometers. 
  The most common substances polluting the ground water are 
petroleum products, phenols, heavy metals (copper, zinc, lead, 
cadmium, nickel, and mercury), sulfates, chlorides, and nitrogen 
compounds. The intensity of pollution in 30 percent of the known 
sites of ground water pollution ranges from 10 to 100 times the 
MAC, and the level of various substances in 12 percent of the 
locations exceeds 100 times the MAC. 
  There is no standard list of substances to be monitored in 
ground water, and this precludes the compilation of a precise 
map of ground water pollution. 
<H5>  1.4. Land Resources and Their Quality, Protection, and Use </H5>
  Russia's land resources in 1992 amounted to 1,709,600,000* 
hectares, including: 
  -- the land of agricultural enterprises and citizens--651 
million* hectares (38.1 percent*); 
  -- the land of populated communities--6.2 million* hectares 
(0.4 percent*); 
  -- the land used for industry, transportation, 
communications, and other nonagricultural purposes--17.7 
million* hectares (1.2 percent*); 
  -- the land of natural preserves--20.7 million* hectares 
(1.2 
percent*); 
  -- the land of forests--878.1 million* hectares (51.4 
percent*); 
  -- the land of water resources--18.1 million* hectares (1 
percent*); 
  -- reserve lands--117.8 million* hectares (6.9 percent*). 
  Changes in the structure of agricultural land resources are 
interesting (Table 1.4.1). 


Table 1.4.1. Changes in Agricultural Land Use Patterns in Russian Federation 

