  As Table 1.4.1 indicates, agricultural land represents 13 
percent of all land resources (222.3 million* hectares). 
  Figure 1.4.1 illustrates the share of total land resources 
occupied by plowed fields. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-28A>           Figure 1.4.1. Percentage of Total </FIG>



  The area of agricultural land decreased by 12.4 million* 
hectares in the last 27 years, including a decrease of 2.3 
million* hectares in plowed fields and 10.6 million* hectares in 
hayfields. The reasons for the reduction of agricultural area 
are the destruction and degradation of topsoil and the inclusion 
of some agricultural land in the territory of cities, 
settlements, and industrial enterprises. 
  Changes in the plowed area in different parts of the Russian 
Federation are presented in Figure 1.4.2. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-28B>           Figure 1.4.2. Changes in 1992 Plowed </FIG>



  Russia's chernozem soils cover an area of around 120 million 
hectares. This is only around 7 percent of the total area, but 
this is the location of more than half of all the plowed fields 
and the source of around 80 percent of all farming products. 
  The distribution of agricultural soils is presented in Table 
1.4.2. 


Table 1.4.2. Structure of Soil Cover of Agricultural Land of Russian 
Federation (percentage of total area) 

Types of soil                  Agricultural land          Plowed fields 

Podzolic and soddy-podzolic    12.3                       14.7 

Soddy and soddy-calcareous     2.4                        1.4 

Gray forest and brown forest   11.8                       14.9 


Chernozem                      42.9                       52.6 

Chestnut                       12.8                       10.6 

Alkaline, saline, and          7.0                        3.4 
degraded solonetz 

Floodplain (alluvial)          4.9                        0.6 

Other                          5.9                        1.8 


<H5>  [No 22, 1993 pp 4-9] </H5>
  Erosion-prone and eroded agricultural land covers an area of 
124 million hectares (56 percent), including 87.3 million 
hectares of plowed fields. According to 1990 state records, 
gullies covered an area of 2.4 million hectares, 26.2 million 
hectares of plowed fields (20.4 percent) were located on eroded 
soils, 2.1 million hectares (1.7 percent) had suffered from the 
combined effects of water and wind erosion, 7.9 million hectares 
(6.1 percent) had been damaged by wind erosion, and all of the 
land prone to wind erosion covered an area of 44 million 
hectares (32.2 percent). Areas of eroded chernozems are growing. 
In the last 15-20 years they have increased by an average of 
250,000-300,000 hectares a year. In many locations with 
chernozem soils, 50 percent or more of the plowed area is 
eroded. The growth of gullies results in the loss of 
25,000-30,000 hectares of chernozem each year. 
  Soil protection efforts have decreased in recent years. 
Shallow cultivation with the retention of stubble on the surface 
was conducted on an area of 19.7 million hectares and 
cross-plowing on inclines was conducted on 13.7 million hectares 
in 1991. These figures were below the 1988 figures by 8.6 
million and 5.9 hectares respectively. Protective forest strips 
were planted on 16,100 fewer hectares in 1992 than in 1991. 
  The productivity of soil is declining in large areas as a 
result of the lower humus content. The supply was reduced by 
25-30 percent in just the last 20 years, and average annual 
losses in the Russian Federation as a whole amount to 81.4 
million tonnes. According to the data of agrochemical 
inspections, 16.5 million hectares of plowed fields in Russia 
are distinguished by an extremely low humus content, and another 
21 million hectares have a low content. The humus content of 
chernozems in the central chernozem oblasts has been reduced by 
almost half in the last 100 years--declining from 10-14 percent 
to 7-10 percent, and annual losses of humus in chernozem soils 
average 0.5-1.0 tonnes per hectare. 
  The area of reclaimed land in an unsatisfactory state has 
been reduced by 105,000 hectares in the Russian Federation as a 
whole. Around 771,000 hectares of irrigated land is in an 
unsatisfactory state, including 325,000 hectares where the water 
table is too deep, 292,000 hectares damaged by salinization, and 
154,000 hectares suffering from a combination of these two 
factors. The total area of saline lands is 38.4 million hectares 
(19.9 percent of all agricultural land), including 25.6 million 
hectares of alkaline-saline soils. Plowed fields with saline 
soils cover an area of 12.9 million hectares. 
  Waterlogged and boggy areas used as plowland are increasing. 
In 1990 they covered 8 million hectares (5.2 percent of the 
plowed fields), whereas there were 5.8 million hectares (or 4.5 
percent) in 1985. 
  Desertification has damaged 4.9 million hectares in 
Kalmykia, 
and 1.8 million of these are in a state of extreme 
desertification. Degraded pastures in Astrakhan Oblast cover an 
area of 1.3 million hectares, including 250,000 hectares of 
shifting sands. Severely and moderately eroded lands occupy 48 
percent of all the pastures. 
  The degradation of pastures also occurs in the tundra zone 
as 
a result of parching, the destruction of the soil cover and the 
vegetative cover during the broad-scale exploitation of mineral 
deposits and the use of the pastures by motor vehicles in 
locations without proper roads, and the overgrazing of 
livestock. Between 1965 and 1990 the area of reindeer grazing 
lands decreased by 20.2 million* hectares. 
  The total area of land damaged by mining, construction, and 
geological prospecting amounted to 1.1 million hectares in 1991, 
including 700,000 hectares damaged between 1976 and 1991. More 
than 50 percent of the area was occupied by agricultural land. 
During this period, 1,341,700 hectares of damaged lands were 
recultivated. 
<H5>  Pollution of the Soil With Pesticides </H5>
  The quantity of pesticides used in agriculture each year did 
not change between 1980 and 1991 and amounted to approximately 
150,000 tonnes. The figure decreased to 100,000 tonnes in 1992. 
  The use of pesticides in the different economic regions of 
the Russian Federation in 1992 is illustrated in Figure 1.4.3. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-30A>           Figure 1.4.3. Use of Pesticides in RF </FIG>



  In Russia as a whole in 1992, soil polluted by pesticides 
was 
found in 5.8 percent of the monitored area of 29,800 hectares in 
spring and in 9.3 percent of the monitored area of 32,000 
hectares in fall. Lower levels of pesticides were recorded in 
the soils of Omsk Oblast in 1992, but the rate of soil pollution 
remained the same in Maritime Kray and Irkutsk, Samara, Rostov, 
and Moscow oblasts. The soil of orchards and forests 
(representing 37-52 percent of the monitored area) was the most 
highly contaminated by pesticide residue (mainly DDT). Fields of 
vegetable crops were polluted by the residue of DDT, 2,4-D, and 
trephalan on 17.7 percent of the area; the soil of grain fields 
was polluted by DDT, HCCH, 2,4-D, propazine, trephalan, and TCNP 
on 11.3 percent of the area. The regions with high levels of 
pollution include Moscow and Irkutsk oblasts, and average levels 
were found in the soils of the Central-Chernozem Region, 
Maritime Kray, the North Caucasus, and Kurgan Oblast. 
Territories with little pollution included Omsk Oblast and all 
but a few oblasts of the Upper Volga and cis-Volga regions. 
<H5>  Pollution of Soils by Toxic Substances of Industrial Origin </H5>
  According to the data of aerospace mapping, the zones of 
dispersion of technogenic emissions around industrial complexes 
cover an area of 18 million hectares, or 1 percent of the total 
area of the Russian Federation. 
  Emissions of pollutants from stationary sources per unit of 
area are illustrated in Figure 1.4.4. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-30B>           Figure 1.4.4. Harmful Emissions from </FIG>



  Although the average maximum figure is 0.2-0.23 
tonnes/km[.sup]2[/], local figures can reach as high as 10 
tonnes/km[.sup]2[/] (in the Ural, Central, and 
Central-Chernozem economic regions). 
  The area of the soil cover polluted by heavy metals and 
fluorine has been estimated at 3.579 billion hectares. 
Territories with a highly polluted soil cover (from 10 to 100 
times the background level) cover an area of 253 million 
hectares. 
  In all of the territories surveyed in 1992, the highest 
level 
of pollution by heavy metals were found in the soil in the 
5-kilometer zone around the city of Rudnaya Pristan, the grounds 
of enterprises in Svirsk and Verkhnyaya Pyshma, and the soils of 
Irkutsk, Cheremkhovo, and Nizhneudinsk. 
  Lead in excess of 10 times the MAC was found in the soils of 
Irkutsk, Svirsk, Rudnaya Pristan, Kamensk-Uralskiy, and 
Cheremkhovo. 
  A copper content 10 times as high as the average was found 
in 
the soil of Zavolzhye, Nizhniy Novgorod, Kirov, Tomsk, and 
Rudnaya Pristan. 
  Vanadium levels exceeding 10 times the MAC were recorded in 
Kirov and Nizhniy Novgorod. 
  Fluorine pollutes the soils around enterprises of the 
aluminum industry in Krasnoturyinsk, Bratsk, Novokuznetsk, 
Volgograd, and Krasnoyarsk. The maximum concentration of total 
fluorine in the soils of these regions is 4-10 times the 
background level, and the level of water-soluble fluorine is 
10-30 times the MAC. 
  The density of atmospheric fluoride precipitation in 1991 
was 
1.5 times as high as the 1983 figure around the Bratsk Aluminum 
Plant, and 4 times the 1983 figure near the Irkutsk plant. 
  The petroleum content of soil in locations of oil 
extraction, 
refining, transport, and distribution is dozens of times as high 
as the background level. 
  The average content of petroleum products in the soils of 
Avtozavodskiy Rayon in Nizhniy Novgorod in 1992 was four times 
as high as the background level, and the content in 7 percent of 
the samples was 10 times as high. The content of petroleum in 
the soil 10 kilometers east and west of Vladimir was 33 times as 
high as the background level. 
  The petroleum content of the grounds of a refinery in 
Volgograd was 13 times as high as the background level, and it 
was 3-19 times as high in the soil of the Omsk Fuel and 
Lubricant Depot. 
<H5>  1.5. Mineral Use and Protection of Mineral Resources </H5>
  Russia ranks high in the world in terms of mineral resource 
potential. The State Commission on Commercial Mineral Deposits 
has approved around 90 percent of all known deposits and 
confirmed their reliability, profitability, and readiness for 
industrial exploitation. 
  Lead, tungsten, antimony, mercury, load and placer gold, 
silver, and phosphorite resources, however, are limited. There 
are almost no reserves of high-grade manganese, chromite, and 
kaolin ore, barite, graphite, and native sulfur. 
  The sharp cuts in exploratory and geological work in the 
last 
five years reduced the Russian Federation's state reserves of 
coal, chromites, lead, nickel in rich sulfide and silicate ores, 
antimony, mercury, platinum, silver, phosphorite, and fluorspar. 
The increase in stocks of bauxite, tin, molybdenum, diamonds, 
barite, apatite, phosphorite, asbestos, and potash salts in 1992 
was not equivalent to the annual output. 
  Although the projected resources of the main types of crude 
minerals are two or three times as great as known reserves, most 
of them are of inferior quality and are located in worse 
geographic and economic conditions. 
  Most of the deposits being worked at this time have large 
stocks of ore of fairly good quality. Stocks of aluminum, lead, 
molybdenum, tungsten, and several nonmetalliferous commercial 
minerals, however, are inferior to foreign supplies. 
  The intensive exploitation of deposits is depleting the 
resource base of many mining enterprises in the old mining 
regions. Iron ore enterprises in the Urals and West Siberia, 
copper, nickel, and bauxite enterprises in the Urals, lead and 
zinc enterprises in the North Caucasus, Transbaykal, and the Far 
East, tin ore enterprises in Maritime and Khabarovsk krays and 
Chukotka, diamond mining enterprises in Yakutia, and most of the 
gold mining enterprises in Siberia cannot develop the necessary 
capacity either because of inadequate resource reserves or 
because of the difficulty of extracting remaining supplies. 
  The output of almost all types of crude minerals has 
decreased since the end of the 1980s, particularly the output of 
oil and coal (Table 1.5.1). 


Table 1.5.1. Output of Main Types of Fuel 

Fuel         1987       1988       1989       1990       1991       1992 

Oil,**       569.5*     568.8*     552.2*     516.2*     462.3*     400.0* 
millions 
of tonnes 

Gas,         544.3*     589.8*     615.8*     640.6*     643.4*     640.5* 
billions 
of cubic 
meters 

Coal,        414.7*     425.5*     409.9*     395.4*     353.3*     337.2* 
millions 
of tonnes 

** Including gas condensate. 


  The reduced output of oil and the lower growth rate in gas 
production are the result of the protracted intensive 
exploitation of highly productive deposits with essentially 
unique reserves and of cuts in capital investments in 
hydrocarbon extraction. 
  Losses of some types of commercial minerals during 
extraction 
and processing are still high. Particularly large quantities are 
lost in the earth in the underground mining of coal (25.7 
percent), including coking coal (18.3 percent), chromium ore 
(27.7 percent), and potash salts (60.1 percent). Losses of 
extracted minerals during processing include more than a third 
of the tin, around one-fourth of the iron, tungsten, molybdenum, 
potassium oxide, and phosphorus pentoxide from phosphorite ores, 
and one-fifth of the lead and zinc. Although the final 
extraction yields in 1992 were higher than the 1991 figures by 
1.4 percent for coking coal, 0.4 percent for iron ore, 0.3 
percent for tungsten-molybdenum ore, and 2.5 percent for potash 
salts, and although concentration recovery figures were 1.9 
percent higher for iron, 1.4 percent higher for zinc, and 0.8 
percent higher for tin, the yield of the majority of commercial 
minerals was nevertheless smaller than in 1987 (tables 1.5.2 and 
1.5.3). 


