  Around 8.2 billion m[.sup]3[/] of casing-head gas burned 
in 1992. The use of this gas during oil extraction was just as 
unsatisfactory as it had been the year before. Losses of sulfur 
from fuel gas and of helium and ethane from natural gas 
increased. 
  The accumulated waste products (45 billion tonnes) of 
ore-dressing enterprises (including more than 10 billion tonnes 
at enterprises of ferrous and nonferrous metallurgy) are not 
being put to satisfactory use. 
  Enterprises were more inclined to practice the selective 
working of the best sections of deposits, which led to the 
accumulation of underground stocks of commercial minerals of 
inferior quality: the Norilskiy Nikel concern (Krasnoyarsk 
Kray), the Tyrnyauz Tungsten-Molybdenum combine 
(Kabardino-Balkar Republic), and the Gaysk Ore-Dressing Combine 
(GOK) (Orenburg Oblast). 
  Because mineral extraction and processing facilities are 
having a destructive effect on the environment, the intelligent 
and comprehensive use of mineral resources is a priority of 
environmental protection in the locations of mining enterprises. 
  The development of the sites of mineral deposits is an acute 
problem in several mining regions. In the Kuzbass, for example, 
each year the sites of coal deposits are developed, but the 
reserves in these deposits exceed 100 million tonnes, and this 
will complicate the working of these deposits in the future. 
Construction projects on the sites of potash salt deposits in 
the damaged left-bank section of the city of Berezniki have 
continued. This problem has to be solved on the federal level, 
specifically by the legislative restriction of construction in 
mining regions. 
  Therefore, the state of affairs in the use of the crude 
mineral base and the protection of mineral resources is still on 
the verge of rapid deterioration. 
  The resolution of many problems in the protection of mineral 
resources is connected directly with the need to improve 
existing laws on mineral resources and the creation of an 
economic mechanism for the intelligent use of these resources. 
  In addition to the unsatisfactory use of commercial minerals 
during the stages of extraction and processing, the prospecting 
and exploitation of deposits can cause irreversible changes in 
the landscape, the appropriation of land, the disruption of 
hydrological patterns, and the pollution of the environment. 
There is a great risk of ecological catastrophes at the time of 
accidents accompanied by emissions, oil spills, and fires in gas 
and oil wells and coal mines. 
<H5>  1.6. Forests and Their Use, Reproduction, and Protection </H5>
  The total area of Russia's forests amounts to 1,182,600,000* 
hectares, including 771 million* hectares of dense forests (65 
percent of the total) with timber reserves of 81.6 billion* 
m[.sup]3[/] (according to forest inventory records). The 
distribution of dense forests in different regions of Russia is 
illustrated in Figure 1.6.1. Russia's forests are mainly 
coniferous--78 percent* (cedar--6.2 percent*), deciduous 
softwood--19 percent*, and deciduous hardwood--3 percent*. The 
total forested area suitable for exploitation (logging 
operations) covers 388.5 million* hectares, or 38 percent* of 
the total, with timber reserves of 47.6 billion* m[.sup]3[/] 
(66 percent*). The area of mature and overmature trees covers 
183.3 million* hectares, with reserves of 29.1 billion* 
m[.sup]3[/]. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-34A>           Figure 1.6.1. Densely Wooded Area </FIG>



  The felling limit (or consumption standard) in the Russian 
Federation as a whole was 542.5 million* m[.sup]3[/] in 1992, 
including 330.2 million* m[.sup]3[/] of conifers. The 
overfelling of conifers, by 1.7 million* m[.sup]3[/], was 
recorded only in Arkhangelsk Oblast. This was done with the 
permission of the oblast administration. 
  The public felling area has decreased from 2 million 
hectares 
in 1988 to 1.4 million* hectares (see Table 1.6.1). There have 
been no significant changes in cutting methods and technologies. 
Clear-cutting is still practiced on around 90 percent* of the 
total cutting area. 


