  The development of market relations is directly jeopardizing 
the survival of Russian fauna. The excessive demand for furs, 
reindeer antlers, bear gall, the musk of the musk deer, and 
other products has resulted in a new outbreak of poaching. The 
illegal hunting of wildlife has become a criminally destructive 
practice. 
  Resources of commercial game animals, such as Kamchatka 
beavers, fur seals, and some other types of seals, are being 
depleted, and the numbers of steppe polecat, lynx, glutton, 
yellow-throated marten, Himalayan bear, wood grouse, bustards, 
predatory birds, and waders are dwindling. The European 
population of saiga, the numbers of some strains of mountain 
sheep and goats, Siberian wildcats, Mongolian gazelle, steppe 
falcon, some species of pheasant, and some other species have 
reached the critical point. 
  Commercial fishing for aquatic invertebrates and the 
collection of snake venom and of rare and endangered species of 
birds and insects are virtually unrestricted. 
  To a considerable extent, this has occurred because the 
functions of government administration and control were not 
separated completely from the functions of resource use, and the 
Law of the RSFSR ``On the Protection and Use of Fauna'' and 
earlier RF Government decisions were not brought into conformity 
with the requirements of the Law of the RSFSR ``On the 
Protection of the Natural Environment.'' Hunting and fishing 
inspection agencies were under separate jurisdiction, were not 
supplied with the most essential materials and equipment, and 
became entangled in the fights over the division of authority 
with agencies of the Russian Ministry of Ecology. 
  As a result, in spite of the widespread violations of 
hunting 
regulations, environmental agencies discovered 15,000 fewer 
cases of poaching in 1992 than in the previous year. There are 
no records of the numbers and bag of even the most common 
species of animals, and information received from various 
sources is extremely fragmented and contradictory. The group of 
fees for the use of animal resources has not been finalized yet. 
  Therefore, the standards and structure of government 
management of animal resources do not meet the requirements of 
the developing market economy, and the commercial use of 
biological resources is acquiring chaotic features and has 
escaped government control. 
<H3>  1.8. Fish Resources and Their Present State, Use, 
Protection, and Reproduction </H3>
  Fresh-water basins in the Russian Federation annually yield 
around 200,000* tonnes of fish. More than 60 percent of the 
catch comes from the basins of large rivers, lakes, and 
reservoirs. Under the conditions of market relations in recent 
years, the leasing of commercial ponds and fishing areas, and 
the sale of fishing licenses for game fish, there has been a 
tendency toward smaller catches (Table 1.8.1). 


Table 1.8.1. Catch of Fish in Largest Rivers, Lakes, and Reservoirs in 
Russian Federation from 1989 to 1992, in thousands of tonnes 

Water basins               1989         1990         1991         1992 

Ob-Irtysh                  16.1         20.4         15.8         14.0 

Yenisey River              3.2          3.4          3.1          3.0 

Lake Ladoga                6.0          5.2          5.0          4.0 

Lake Onega                 3.0          2.1          2.8          1.9 

Lake Pskovsko-Chudskoye    10.5         6.8          6.4          4.6 

Lake Ilmen                 2.9          2.2          3.1          3.3 

Lake Baykal                4.1          3.7          4.1          3.8 

Rybinskoye Reservoir       2.8          2.3          2.6          1.9** 

Kuybyshev Reservoir        6.0          5.5          5.2          4.3 

Saratov Reservoir          1.8          1.9          1.9          1.8 

Volgograd Reservoir        5.0          4.2          3.6          2.2 

Tsimlyansk Reservoir       15.9         13.1         12.6         9.6 

** In 10 months. 


  Fish stocks in the waters of the Ob-Irtysh basin, 
including the Obsk and Tazov coves, are in unsatisfactory 
condition, except for the whitefish. Feeding conditions have 
been affected adversely in the last three years by the drop in 
the water level. The catch of commercial game fish--nelma, 
muksun, and peliad--is decreasing. The catch of whitefish 
depends on fishing conditions and the organization of fisheries. 
The catch in remote regions has decreased dramatically. 
  The Yenisey River, with its low level of 
biological productivity, is marked by the dramatic reduction of 
the supply and catch of the main commercial species--whitefish 
and sig--due to the regulation of runoff from the Krasnoyarsk 
GES. 
  There are strict limits on sturgeon, nelma, salmon trout, 
and 
sig fishing in the Lena River. The catch of sig is 
being reduced by the effects of industrial sewage. The total 
catch can only be increased by the addition of small fish caught 
in fine-mesh nets and crucian carp. 
  In most lakes the catch of commercial species--salmon, 
whitefish, and fish caught in large nets (pike perch, pike, and 
even bream in some cases)--is far in excess of allowable limits, 
whereas reserves of species with less commercial value are 
underutilized. This is causing undesirable changes in the 
composition of ichthyofauna, replacing valuable species with 
roach, perch, and ruff. 
  In Lake Ladoga, which has been affected severely 
by industrial and household sewage, reserves of sig are being 
reduced by the eutrophication of the lake. Stocks of small fish 
are underutilized. The catch of smelt is increasing, but the 
catch of pike perch, bream, and pike is decreasing. 
  In Lake Onega the resource base could yield a 
sizable catch of smelt and whitefish--the main commercial fish. 
The reduction of the catch is due to economic factors. 
  Stocks of whitefish in Lake Pskovsko-Chudskoye can 
be described as small, and reserves of sig are smaller than in 
earlier years. Stocks of pike perch and pike are satisfactory. 
The intense pollution of the lake with petroleum products, 
phenols, and heavy metal salts and the loss of most of the fish 
in winter have affected the natural reproduction of these 
reserves and the size of stocks and catches. 
<H5>  [No 23, 1993 pp 5-12] </H5>
  Lake Ilmen is distinguished by stable reserves of 
bream and satisfactory reserves of pike. The number of pike 
perch has decreased perceptibly, resulting in the institution of 
a fishing limit. More than 50 percent of the catch in the lake 
consists of small fish. 
  A fishing limit on omul, the main commercial fish in Lake 
Baykal, has resulted in the efficient use of omul 
reserves. Reserves of burbot are satisfactory. The catch limit 
on pike, ide, and carp is the result of the poor organization of 
hatcheries and the plundering of these species. 
<H5>  Volga Reservoirs </H5>
  Stocks of pelagian fish are increasing in the 
Rybinskoye Reservoir because of the growth of the 
supply of plankton in connection with the eutrophication of the 
basin. The catch of bottom fish is decreasing, and particularly 
quickly in the case of burbot and pike, as a result of the 
pollution of the reservoir by the Cherepovets Metallurgical 
Combine. 
  Stocks of bream are in a satisfactory state in the 
Kuybyshev Reservoir and constitute 35 percent of the 
total catch here. The reduced catch of pike, catfish, and burbot 
is connected with organizational difficulties. Reserves of small 
fish are being underutilized. 
  Bream reserves are stable in the Saratov 
Reservoir. Stocks of pike perch and pike are small because they 
are highly vulnerable to unfavorable hydrological conditions 
during the spawning season. Sterlet stocks have been stable 
since the fishery opened in 1989. The total yield is close to 
the optimum. Reserves of small fish are being underutilized. 
Herbivorous fish are accounting for an ever greater percentage 
of the catch, and the stocks of these have been estimated at 
1,500-1,700 tonnes. 
  Reserves of the main species in the Volgograd 
Reservoir have been given a satisfactory rating. The reduced 
catch is due to the high water level in recent years. Supplies 
of herbivorous fish and small fish are being underutilized. 
  The Tsimlyansk Reservoir has also acquired 
commercial significance. Reserves of most species have a 
satisfactory rating. Bream is the main fish here, and the total 
catch depends on the state of bream stocks. The catch in recent 
years has amounted to 5,000-6,000 tonnes. It is a limited 
species along with pike perch and blue bream. The carp 
populations are small. 
<H5>  Marine Basins </H5>
  The total catch of fish in the Barents Sea was 
around 600,000 tonnes (including 400,000 tonnes of capelin), as 
compared to 520,000 tonnes in 1991. The cod catch increased from 
114,000 tonnes (1991) to 170,000 (1992) as a result of the 
gradual growth of commercial reserves in the seas of the 
northeast Atlantic. 
  Commercial stocks of haddock (330,000 tonnes) were below the 
average, and stocks of black halibut (around 80,000 tonnes), 
brown snapper (215,000 tonnes), plaice (around 30,000 tonnes), 
and anarhichas species were low. Stocks of capelin decreased 
from 7 million tonnes to 5.5 million. There were also reduced 
stocks of commercial shellfish--scallops and shrimp, although 
the state of shrimp reserves is excellent. 
  Other seas of the Arctic Ocean have no commercial 
significance because they have not been explored sufficiently, 
mainly because of the climate. 
  The numbers of Baltic sprat are still increasing in the 
Baltic Sea. Commercial reserves of this fish in the 
Russian part of the sea reached 725,000 tonnes. Most of the 
herring populations are in excellent condition. Stocks of East 
Baltic cod, however, are in a critical state: Spawning reserves 
have decreased to almost one-seventh of the earlier figure in 
the last 10 years--from 776,000 tonnes in 1983 to 115,000 in 
1992. Stocks of salmon are decreasing. 
  The catch of fish in the Black Sea in 1992 
remained small and amounted to only around 28,000 tonnes, 
including around 12,000 tonnes of anchovy and 13,800 tonnes of 
sprat. Stocks of Black Sea sprat have improved since they began 
decreasing in 1991. The supply in 1992 was 500,000 tonnes. 
Stocks of perch and gray mullet are in a depressed state. 
  Commercial stocks of plaice (1,100 tonnes in 1992) and of 
Azov-Don herring are in a depressed state in the Azov 
Sea. Commercial stocks of sandre amount to 15,000 tonnes, the 
lowest figure of the last decade. Azov anchovy stocks amounted 
to 90,000 tonnes in 1992, and the Russian catch was 2,700 
tonnes. Supplies of sea roach are low. The populations of common 
and starred sturgeon were satisfactory. 
  In the Caspian Sea there was a large catch of 
bream--13,700 tonnes--and Caspian roach--19,900 tonnes. The 
catch of sandre increased in all regions. Stocks of carp and 
catfish were in good condition. The catch of sturgeon in Russia 
amounted to 7,300 tonnes, including 4,240 tonnes of common 
sturgeon, 2,560 tonnes of starred sturgeon, and 460 tonnes of 
beluga. The beluga displayed privation bordering on starvation. 
Commercial stocks of sterlet were estimated at 230,600 fish. 
There was still a tendency toward decrease in the sprat 
catch--168,000 tonnes in 1992 (the lowest of the last 25 years 
because of reduced breeding efforts). 
  The basins of the Sea of Okhotsk, the Sea of 
Japan, and the Bering Sea and the adjacent 
open expanses of the northwestern Pacific now yield half of the 
Russian catch. 
  In the maritime economic zone of Russia's Far Eastern seas, 
90 percent of the catch consists of mintai, salmon, herring, 
cod, plaice, whitefish, and pollack. Mintai accounts for 71 
percent of the catch, but the stocks of mintai have decreased 
substantially in recent years, particularly in the Bering Sea, 
because of the mismanagement of fisheries. Fishing has been more 
intense in the open expanses of the Sea of Okhotsk, including 
the fishing boats of foreign states. The populations of mintai 
in that sea will be undermined unless mintai fishing in the open 
part of the sea is restricted. 
  Commercial stocks of Far East salmon are average or low, but 
the latest data on the state of certain populations attest to an 
increase in their numbers. 
  The number of Pacific herring is still low, and this will 
require the maintenance of fishing limits. 
  Stocks of cod have increased almost everywhere in the Far 
East in recent years, but the size of the populations near the 
southern Kurils is still on the low 1991 level. 
  An increase in reserves of plaice, primarily yellowfin, has 
been recorded on the West Kamchatka shelf. The rate of sardine 
reproduction in 1992 was much higher than in the previous year. 
A tendency toward the reduction of Iwashi sardine stocks has 
been noted in recent years. The high numbers of pollack fry and 
their excellent rate of survival promise large stocks. 
  Most of the stocks of commercial shellfish are concentrated 
in the seas of the Far East. Stocks of Kamchatka crab, beetle 
crab, blue crab, and spiny crab in 1992 were the same as in 
1991. Tawbatch fishing is still prohibited. Three species of 
squid are of commercial value. Domestic fishermen concentrate on 
the commodore squid, the stocks of which are stable. Reserves of 
Far Eastern brown algae are the largest in Russia, but not all 
of them are in accessible locations, and the algae supply in 
traditional fishing areas has been reduced sharply by 
unrestricted fishing and by game violations. 
  Calculations of the size of populations of sea mammals in 
the 
waters of Russia in 1992 did not reveal any significant changes 
in the state of these resources since the previous year. 
According to International Whaling Commission data, the Pacific 
gray whales of the Chukotka-California population now number 
around 20,100. 
  The fur seal population of the Commodore Islands will 
stabilize at around 225,000-230,000 seals in the next few years. 
The population in the Sea of Okhotsk is in a stable-depressed 
state and numbers around 59,000 fur seals. 
  The total number of seals in the Sea of Okhotsk is around 
1.3 
million (545,000 akiba, 405,000 fascia, 180,000 largo, and 
180,000 lachta). 
<H5>  Reproduction of Fish Resources </H5>
  At this time 114 state fisheries--sturgeon and salmon 
hatcheries, small fish farms, spawning and breeding farms, 
production-acclimatization stations, and others--are engaged in 
the reproduction of fish resources. 
  In 1992 these enterprises put more than 7.15 billion fry in 
natural ponds and reservoirs, including 104.1 million sturgeon, 
637.5 million salmon, 59.4 million sig, and 6.34 billion small 
fish and herbivorous fish. 
  Around 1.026 billion Atlantic salmon fry were released into 
the northern basin for the reproduction of stocks. 
  Most of the sturgeon and small fish fry in the Caspian and 
Azov basins come from hatcheries. Stocks of white and red salmon 
in the Caspian Sea are maintained exclusively by means of 
artificial reproduction. As a result, around 30 percent of the 
fish in the Caspian basin and more than 80 percent of the fish 
in the Azov basin come from fish farms. 
  The artificial reproduction of Pacific salmon was conducted 
at fish farms in Sakhalin, Kamchatka, and Magadan oblasts and 
Maritime and Khabarovsk krays, which produced more than 630 
million fry of humpbacked, calico, silver, and red salmon. 
  The artificial reproduction of fish stocks puts around 
70,000 
tonnes back into circulation each year. 
  The development of the artificial reproduction of fish 
stocks 
is being impeded by the progressive pollution of sources of 
water. This destroys much of the breeding stock in hatcheries, 
and the surviving fry do not always satisfy the necessary 
requirements. 
  In 1992 virtually no measures were taken to improve the 
conditions of the natural reproduction of fish resources. 
Hatchery construction and remodeling projects were suspended. 
<H5>  Effects of Ecological State of Basins on Fish Resources </H5>
  The state of fish reserves depends on the degree of 
anthropogenic influence on the ecosystems of water basins. 
  The White and Barents sea basins: There 
is no commercial fishing in Kola Bay because of severe surface 
and ground water pollution. The whole Kola River, the largest 
salmon spawning bed in Murmansk Oblast, is polluted. 
  Fish stocks in the Pechora River basin are in a depressed 
state as a result of the dumping of industrial sewage, 
stream-driving, and the extraction of sand and gravel. The catch 
of sig and nelma is only one-third or one-fourth of the previous 
level. 
  There have been changes in the ichthyofauna of the Northern 
Dvina River--the percentage of salmon and sig in the catch 
decreased from 29 percent in 1985 to 7.4 percent in 1990. In the 
Onega River the catch of plaice was 27 times larger in the 
1960's than it is now, and the catch of salmon and sig was more 
than 8 times as great in the 1960's. Salmon fishing in the river 
has been prohibited since 1989. 
  The Baltic basin: The pollution of coastal areas 
in Kaliningrad Oblast is localized and is not having a 
perceptible effect on the size of the catch yet. 
  In the eastern part of the Gulf of Riga the content of 
several heavy metals in the fish is approaching the maximum 
allowable concentration and is jeopardizing fishing in these 
regions. 
  Pollution has reduced the effectiveness of salmon and sig 
spawning in Lake Ladoga, and the reproduction of bream has 
deteriorated dramatically in the Petrokrepostnaya inlet. 
  The Azov basin: The regulation of runoff from the 
Don and Kuban rivers by power engineering and irrigation systems 
and the removal of up to 30 percent of the average annual flow 
have caused the severe deterioration of the conditions of 
natural reproduction for the main commercial fish of the Azov 
basin. The spawning beds of semianadromous fish are one-third 
their earlier size, and the spawning beds of anadromous fish are 
almost one-tenth of the earlier size. The length of submerged 
beds has decreased to almost one-fourth of the previous figure. 
Changes in continental runoff have changed the mechanism by 
which the sea is supplied with biogenic elements. 
  The pollution of coastal waters with pesticides has led to 
the accumulation of these substances in the organs and tissues 
of fish (sturgeon, sandre, and carp). 
  The reduction of continental runoff and the increasing 
pollution of the sea have led to the asphyxiation of aquatic 
animals and the death of fish and even of dolphins. 
  The operation of various types of water works is having an 
adverse effect on the state of fish resources in the Azov basin. 
The number of these installations now exceeds 1,500. 
  All of this has reduced the food supply of fish to one-half 
or one-fourth of the previous amount, and reduced the total 
catch to 60,000-120,000 tonnes, including the catch of 
commercial fresh-water fish, which was from 16 to 30 times 
(depending on the species) larger when the continental runoff 
was regulated by natural forces. The beluga and whitefish are 
almost gone. 
  The Black Sea basin: Because of the 
near-disappearance of the Azov anchovy in the Azov Sea as a 
result of the proliferation of Acnidaria, there has been 
virtually no anchovy fishing in the Black Sea for the last three 
years, although the catch here once amounted to more than 60,000 
tonnes. 
  The Caspian basin: The dramatic daily and weekly 
fluctuations in the water level, current, and temperature as a 
result of the winter operations of the Volgograd GES have 
disrupted sturgeon wintering conditions downstream of the GES. 
This has led to the resorption of roe in more than 18 percent of 
the female sturgeon and more than 21 percent of the beluga. 
These sturgeon do not spawn the next season, and this has a 
damaging effect on natural reproduction. 
  The state of fish resources is affected adversely by the 
regular pollution of the water in the Volga basin and by the 
operation of water works with defective devices for the 
protection of fish or without these devices. There are more than 
4,000 registered water intakes of various types in the Caspian 
basin: 1,900 are equipped with special devices for the 
protection of fish, 2,000 have primitive protective devices, and 
100 have no means of protecting fish. 
  The basin of the Far Eastern seas: Industrial 
sewage has polluted 55 percent of the salmon spawning beds in 
the rivers of Sakhalin Oblast. The receding water level of the 
Bolshoy Takoy River as a result of the drainage of bogs upstream 
has reduced the number of fertile autumn Pacific salmon in the 
river to a fraction of what it was. 
  The continued deterioration of ecological conditions in the 
rivers of the Far East could cause irretrievable losses of 
salmon, which, along with the sturgeon, are Russia's national 
treasures. 
<H5>  1.9. Radioactive Pollution </H5>
  The main source of the radioactive pollution of the 
environment in Russia in 1992 was still the soil of the 
territories contaminated by the accidents at the Chernobyl AES 
in 1986 and the Mayak Production Association in 1957. Winds 
lifting the radioactive dust from the soil and atmospheric 
precipitation washing it out of the soil released radionuclides 
into the air, water, and vegetative ground cover. The background 
radiation far away from these regions is the result of the 
pollution of the air everywhere by the products of earlier 
nuclear tests in the atmosphere. The influence of other 
technogenic factors was negligible and strictly localized. 
<H5>  Radioactive Pollution of the Lower Atmosphere </H5>
  The average concentration of total beta-activity in the 
lower 
atmosphere in 1992 in Russia was around 4.6x10-15 
mc/m[.sup]3[/], which was virtually the same as the 1991 
average. 
  Outside the zones contaminated by the Chernobyl and Kyshtym 
disasters the average concentration of such radionuclides as 
cesium-137 and strontium-90 in the air was 0.4x10-15 and 
0.006x10-15 c/m[.sup]3[/] respectively--i.e., virtually the 
same as before the accident at the Chernobyl AES. 
  The average rate of cesium-137 precipitation was 0.05 
c/km[.sup]2[/] a year, which was approximately half the 1991 
figure. The content of strontium-90 in atmospheric precipitation 
was below the level of detectability by methods of analyzing 
this isotope. 
  The average concentration of krypton-85 from the emissions 
of 
enterprises of the nuclear fuel cycle in the lower atmosphere 
was 24x10-12 c/m[.sup]3[/] of dry air in 1992--i.e., the same 
as last year's figure. 
  The average concentration of tritium in atmospheric 
precipitation was 108x10-12 c/l, which was mainly a result of 
global factors. 
  In Kursk the average annual concentration of cesium-137 in 
the air was 0.25x10-15 c/m[.sup]3[/], and the figure in 
Bryansk was 0.17x10-15 c/m[.sup]3[/], which is below the 
cumulative tolerance dose for this isotope by six orders of 
magnitude. 
  The content of radionuclides in atmospheric precipitation in 
the contaminated territories of the ETR is far in excess of the 
national average. Average daily readings of total beta-activity 
and cesium-137 were 0.07 and 0.05 mc/m[.sup]2[/] in 
Novozybkiy and the maximum daily figures were 8 and 17 
mc/m[.sup]2[/] respectively. 
  There were no perceptible changes in levels of radioactive 
pollution on the grounds of nuclear power plants and other 
installations categorized as radiation hazards in 1992. The 
radiometric network of observation posts of Roskomgidromet [RF 
Committee on Hydrometeorology] did not record the presence of 
iodine-131 in the air or in atmospheric precipitation, in spite 
of the radioactive iodine released into the atmosphere at the 
Ignalina AES (22 July 1992) and the Sverdlovsk branch of the 
Scientific Research and Design Institute of Electrothermal 
Equipment. There were no nuclear tests in Russia in 1992. 
  A surface nuclear explosion of around 1 megaton, conducted 
outside Russia on 21 April 1992 on the PRC test site near Lop 
Nor, did not cause any perceptible changes in the global 
radioactive background last year. 
<H5>  Radioactive Pollution of Territories </H5>
  The accumulation of radioisotope precipitate in the soil 
during the year was negligible everywhere in comparison with the 
total supply in the soil and had virtually no effect on the 
pollution levels that had been recorded at the end of 1991. 
  Projects in 1992 corrected some data in the 1991 report and 
expanded the boundaries of the zones of radioactive pollution by 
cesium-137 (Figure 1.9.1). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-47A>           Figure 1.9.1. Density of Cesium-137 </FIG>



  Most of the radionuclides from Chernobyl were cesium-137 and 
strontium-90, and the rate of soil pollution by strontium was 
from one-fortieth to one-one hundredth of the rate for cesium. 
  The radioactive pollution of territories as of January 1993, 
according to Rosgidromet [Russian Federal Service on 
Hydrometeorology and Environmental Control] data, and the 
population of these territories, according to the lists of the 
populated communities within the zones of radioactive pollution, 
are presented in Table 1.9.1. 


Table 1.9.1. Area of Zones in Russian Oblasts with Ce-137 Pollution Rate of 
